<HEADLINE> Egyptian Parliament Delegation Postpones Visit to Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 18 (Xinhua) -- An Egyptian parliament delegation
decided to postpone a visit to Israel scheduled for today because
of recent tension in Israeli-Palestinian relations, the Middle
East News Agency (MENA) reported.
</P>
<P>
MENA quoted an unidentified diplomatic source as saying here
today that the visit is expected to take place shortly as the
relations have begun to improve following the Summit of
Peacemakers held in the Egyptian Red Sea resort of Sharm el-Sheikh
last Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The world leaders attending the summit, co-chaired by Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak and his U.S. counterpart Bill Clinton,
called for joint efforts to save the Middle East peace process and
fight terrorism.
</P>
<P>
There has been tension in Israeli-Palestinian relations
following four suicide bombings in Israel in a nine-day period
since February 25. The Islamic Resistance Movement (Hamas) claimed
responsibility for the attacks, which killed 58 people.
</P>
<P>
Israel suspended negotiations with the Palestinians and imposed
closure on the West Bank and Gaza Strip in the wake of the attacks.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has blasted Israeli punitive measures against the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The parliament delegation was to be headed by Mohammed
Abdellah, head of the foreign affairs committee in the People's
Assembly (parliament). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
