<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-18 19:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt, Lebanon to Strengthen Trade Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Egypt and Lebanon will accelerate
steps to work out a new agreement on promoting trade ties between
the two countries, according to an Egyptian-Lebanese joint
communique here today.
</P>
<P>
The communique was issued at the end of a three-day visit to
Egypt by Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik Al-Hariri, who headed a
high-ranking delegation including the ministers of agriculture,
industry and oil, economy and trade and minister of state for
financial affairs.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, Hariri discussed with Egyptian officials
means of increasing volume of bilateral trade, which now stands at
some 80 million U.S. dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
Hariri, during a meeting with Egyptian and Lebanese businessmen
here today, said that bilateral economic ties need to be enhanced
as they have not matched the two countries' strong political and
cultural relations.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that bilateral relations are developing in the
best interest of the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Also today, in an address to members of the U.S. Chamber of
Commerce in Cairo, Hariri said that Lebanon will establish a large
free trade zone at Beirut Airport within three years, and will
help market Egyptian products through the zone.
</P>
<P>
Hariri also called for the strengthening of inter-Arab economic
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
During Hariri's visit, the two sides discussed setting up a
joint chamber of commerce and encouraging exchange of visits
between the two countries' businessmen.
</P>
<P>
In the communique, Egypt and Lebanon also stressed the
importance of making efforts for the continuation of the Middle
East peace process on all tracks to establish a just and
comprehensive peace in the region.
</P>
<P>
The communique called on Israel to withdraw from south Lebanon
and the Syrian Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also underlined the need for acknowledging the
legitimate rights of the Palestinian people to self-determination
and establishing their independent state.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, Hariri signed with his Egyptian counterpart Kamal
el-Ganzouri one agreement on encouraging mutual investments and
anther on preventing dual taxation.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on the day, Hariri met with Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak in the southern city of Aswan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
