<HEADLINE> Central Government Will Send No One to Supervise SAR  -- Chinese Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 18 (Xinhua) -- A senior Chinese official said
here today that there will be no one to be sent by the Chinese
Central Government to supervise the work of the government of the
Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) after 1997.
</P>
<P>
Answering reporters' questions at a gathering of Hong Kong
Wushu Union, Zhang Junsheng, deputy director of Xinhua News Agency
Hong Kong Branch, said that the Chinese government will resolutely
carry out the principle of "one country, two systems" and "Hong
Kong people running Hong Kong" after 1997.
</P>
<P>
He said that "one country, two systems" is a consistent
principle of the Chinese government and it has been written into
the Sino-British Joint Declaration and expounded in the Basic law.
</P>
<P>
On the question of the "through train" for the Legislative
council, Zhang said that the "through train" has been destroyed by
the British Hong Kong Authorities and the term of Hong Kong's last
legislative council will expire on June 30, 1997.
</P>
<P>
The "through train" refers to the original arrangement between
the Chinese and British sides for Hong Kong's transition around
1997.
</P>
<P>
He said that even if a "through train" still existed, the term
of the last Legislative Council would likewise expire on June 30,
1997, and could not last beyond that date.
</P>
<P>
He explained that if the election of the last Legislative
Council were conducted in line with the Basic Law, and the
qualification of the members of the council met with the related
stipulations of China's National People's Congress, the members of
the council could shift to serve on the first Legislative Council
of the Hong Kong SAR with a two-year tenure after obtaining the
approval of SAR's Preparatory Committee.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, he said, the issue of the so-called four-year
tenures for members of the last Legislative Council did not exist
from the very beginning.
</P>
<P>
When asked about an appeal for the so-called compensation for
the legislative council members who can not "ride on the through
train", he said that it is simply a "colossal absurdity."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960318.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-18 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Thai PM's Visit to Myanmar Enhances Bilateral Ties (by Zhang Yunfei) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Thai Prime Minister Banharn
Silpa-Archa's two-day official visit to Myanmar has further
enhanced bilateral relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
A joint communique issued at the end of Banharn's visit this
evening said the visit marked "the beginning of a new chapter in
the bilateral relations of Myanmar and Thailand in their efforts
to further promote the friendly relations and mutually beneficial
cooperation between their two countries and peoples."
</P>
<P>
The visit, the first by a Thai prime minister to Myanmar since
1980, followed the 12th Myanmar-Thai Regional Border Committee's
meeting last month in the southeastern Myanmar city of Mawlamyine,
at which progress was made in resolving some border issues between
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
As a friendly gesture on the eve of Banharn's visit, Myanmar
Saturday reopened two of the three border checkpoints at
Tachilek-Maesai and Kawthaung-Ranong. A third one at
Myawaddy-Maesot will be reopened on March 19.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, Chairman of the State Law and Order
Restoration Council (SLORC) and Prime Minister of Myanmar Senior
General Than Shwe met the Thai prime minister and held talks with
him on strengthening bilateral relations as well as on enhancing
regional cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders also witnessed the signing of a border trade
agreement between the two countries. Myanmar has already signed
similar border trade accords with neighboring China, India and
Bangladesh since 1988.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, the Myanmar side has agreed to release some
100 Thais or have their sentences commuted as a gesture to mark
the 50th anniversary of Thai King Bhumibol Adulyadej's ascension
to the throne.
</P>
<P>
Thai Deputy Minister for Agriculture and Cooperatives Monthon
Kri Watnussorn, who accompanied Banharn during the visit, also met
Myanmar Deputy Minister for Livestock Breeding and Fisheries U
Aung Thein and discussed with him on fish and prawn breeding.
</P>
<P>
As a member of the Association of Southeast Asian nations
(ASEAN), Thailand also plays a leading role with its "constructive
engagement" policy in supporting Myanmar's endeavors of joining
ASEAN by inviting Myanmar leader Senior General Than Shwe to last
year's 5th ASEAN summit and Myanmar Foreign Minister U Ohn Gyaw to
the 27th ASEAN ministerial meeting in 1994 in Bangkok as guests of
the host country.
</P>
<P>
Thailand, which is the 4th largest foreign investor in Myanmar
after Britain, Singapore and France, had an investment totaling
443.87 million US dollars in 30 projects in Myanmar at the end of
1995.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
