<DOCNO> XIE19960318.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-18 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OAU Observers Satisfied With Election In Comoros </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The observer mission of the
Organization of African Unity (OAU) said today that the second
round of the presidential election held in the Comoros last
Saturday was fair and peaceful.
</P>
<P>
An OAU report said the presidential election was "a decisive
stage" in the implementation of the Antananarivo Agreement
brokered by the OAU.
</P>
<P>
Mohamed Taki, who had been briefly installed as co-president
by a mercenary force which invaded the Comoros last September, on
Sunday emerged as winner of the presidential elections in the
coup-prone Comoros Island in the Indian Ocean.
</P>
<P>
Taki succeeded Said Mohamed Djohar, who was arrested and
deposed by the mercenary invasion force, and was freed a week
later when the French troops landed and ousted the mercenaries
led by Bob Denard.
</P>
<P>
The OAU observers come from Algeria, Egypt, Ethiopia, Libya,
Madagascar, Mauritius, South Africa and the OAU General
Secretariat. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960318.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-18 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
