<HEADLINE> Compromise on New LSE System Likely </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The London Stock Exchange (LSE)
board is likely to decide to introduce order-driven share dealing
initially for large companies' stocks only when it meets this
week, local press reports said today.
</P>
<P>
Directors are expected to vote in favor of moving to the
controversial order-driven system, which matches buyers and
sellers by computer, but they may at first limit it to the FT-SE
100 shares, and they will continue to allow market- making firms
to deal outside the system in large stakes.
</P>
<P>
The LSE board will meet on Thursday, a day after chairman John
Kemp-Welch is called back to be questioned by MPs of the Treasury
select committee about the exchange's future and the reasons for
sacking chief executive Michael Lawrence last January. MPs were
not satisfied with his answers last month.
</P>
<P>
Lawrence's proposal to move to order-driven dealing was opposed
by the market-making firms. The likely outcome of this week's
board meeting, at which the large market-making firms are strongly
represented, will be a compromise which retains a role for them.
</P>
<P>
Smaller companies' stocks could be brought onto an
order-dealing system later, depending on the reception of market
users to dealing that way in FT-SE 100 shares. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
