<HEADLINE> Christopher Meets Balkan Leaders to Push Dayton Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, March 18 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State Warren
Christopher is meeting three Balkan leaders here Monday afternoon
in a bid to maintain pressure to implementation of the Bosnian
peace agreements.
</P>
<P>
Attending the meetings at the U.S. mission in Geneva are
President Slobodan Milosevic of Serbia, Franjo Tudjman of Croatia
and Acting President Ejup Ganic of Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
High Representative Carl Bildt who also attended the meetings
told reporters earlier this afternoon that although the
Croatian-Bosnian Federation has come upon some serious problems at
the moment, he did not fear that the federation could fall apart.
</P>
<P>
Ganic told reporters before the meetings that he would suggest
to conduct reviews of the implementation of the Dayton agreement
every week. But he did not mention how to do so and at which
level.
</P>
<P>
"There is no crisis at the moment, but we have to look for
methods of surveillance for the implementation of the Dayton
accords," Ganic said.
</P>
<P>
So far the Dayton agreement has been basically honored on the
military aspects but faces a number of setbacks with regard to the
Croatian-Bosnian Federation, the return of refugees and elections.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government, which regards the implementation of the
peace agreements as a top priority in the year of presidential
elections, has been trying hard to break the current deadlock.
</P>
<P>
Before the afternoon talks between Christopher and the three
Balkan leaders, representatives of the Contact Group on Bosnia
also met in Geneva in the morning at the initiative of the United
States to prepare for the afternoon talks.
</P>
<P>
Russia, who had threatened to boycott the contact group meeting
because it had not been consulted beforehand, finally sent an
observer to attend the meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
