<HEADLINE> Mandela Divorce Hearing To Go Ahead </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The divorce case between
South African President Nelson Mandela and his estranged wife
Winnie will go ahead without delay, a supreme court judge said
here today.
</P>
<P>
Justice Frikkie Eloff said he had denied a postponement
requested by Winnie's attorney, Ishmael Semenya, who said the
couple still had a chance for reconciliation and that Winnie had
not yet be informed of the details of Mandela's personal assets.
</P>
<P>
"I don't see any reason why action for divorce should not
proceed," said the judge, adding that President Mandela had
already made up his mind to end the 38-year marriage.
</P>
<P>
However, Eloff ordered that Mandela's lawyers report the
president's assets to Winnie's lawyers by Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, Semenya said the couple should try
mediation by Mr. Mandela's relative, chief paramount Kaizer
Matanzima, in terms of customary law.
</P>
<P>
Mandela, 78, married Winnie Madizikela in 1958. The couple
separated in 1992, two years after Mandela's release from 27
years' imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
Winnie has asked for half of her husband's assets as part of
the condition for the divorce, claiming she contributed to his
wealth during their marriage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
