<HEADLINE> Pan-African Youth Conference Opens In Addis Ababa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The first pan-African
conference on youth and development opened today at Africa Hall
in Addis Ababa.
</P>
<P>
With the theme "the African youth in the 1990s and beyond:
peace, participation and development", the five-day meeting will
mainly discuss issues concerning integration of African youth in
development with emphasis on environment, employment, health,
education, peace and democratization process.
</P>
<P>
The conference is jointly organized by the Organization of
African Unity (OAU), the Economic Commission for Africa (ECA) and
the Pan-African Youth Movement.
</P>
<P>
In his opening address, Ethiopian Deputy Prime Minister
Tamirat Layne said: "Young people of Africa hold the future of
peace and development of this continent in their hands."
</P>
<P>
But "too many children and young people of Africa are not
getting the opportunity to attend school" he pointed out, noting
"it is difficult to expect African economies to develop...when
our youths are neither acquiring the necessary skills nor are
able to find productive employment."
</P>
<P>
"The African youth population is projected to increase by
nearly 40 percent between 1990 and the year 2000," according to
the Ethiopian deputy prime minister.
</P>
<P>
"If we equip them with the pre-requisite technical knowledge
and skills, I believe African youth can adequately deal with the
numerous and complex challenges of the modern world," he
declared.
</P>
<P>
OAU and ECA officials, on their parts, appealed to the African
youth to participate in the peace activities and development of
the continent.
</P>
<P>
ECA Deputy Executive Secretary M. Sarr said that "young people
have been forced to the centre of many of Africa's internal
conflicts, as fighters or victims".
</P>
<P>
"Investment in youth is the insurance policy for the world of
the 21st century," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
