<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Government Spending keeps rising Last year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 18 (Xinhua) -- U.S. government spending kept
rising last year even as President Clinton was cutting the Federal
payroll, The New York times reported today.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government spent 103 billion dollars in 1995 in salary
and expenses for its employees, according to an official of the
Office of Management and Budget. That is a very slight decline,
about 1 billion dollars, from its payroll costs in 1994 and 1993.
</P>
<P>
But the dollar value of U.S. government's contracts with
private companies reached to 114 billion dollars last year, more
than a 3.5 percent rise a year since 1993.
</P>
<P>
President Clinton has referred frequently to the elimination of
more than 200,000 government positions--about 10 percent of the
Federal work force--during his 3-year tenure of office. "The era
of big government is over," said the president in his State of
Union Message earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
But the report said that while those jobs have vanished on
paper, many of the responsibilities are being fulfilled by outside
private contracts and little money has been saved.
</P>
<P>
Eliminating Federal jobs and giving them to private contractors
is a trend not only at rapidly shrinking agencies such as the
Ministry of Defense, but at departments that are still growing
like Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
U.S. government plans to cede broad new law-enforcement
responsibilities to private contractors, who will run most of new
government prisons but will not be subject to Federal rules.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960318.0026 </DOCNO>
