<HEADLINE> HKWU Chief: Make Wushu Olympic Sport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 18 (Xinhua) -- All people in Wushu (Martial
Arts) should unite to make the sport an Olympic discipline, head
of the Hong Kong Wushu Union said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Ian C. W. Fok, president of the Union, said their present task
is to put Wushu into the competition program for the Bangkok Asian
Games in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The sport had been included in the Asian Games in 1990 in
Beijing and in the 1994 Games in Hiroshima, Japan.
</P>
<P>
However, Fok said the long-term goal for the sport is to make
it an Olympic event.
</P>
<P>
To this end, Fok said the Hong Kong Wushu Association and the
Chinese Wushu Assiociation have made great common efforts.
</P>
<P>
Anthony H.Y. Wan, member of the Union's newly-elected executive
board, said that Wushu's world governing body World Wushu
Federation has perhaps more than 75 members, which were the
minimum needed to apply for making an Olympic sport.
</P>
<P>
"We are optimistic," he said.
</P>
<P>
Wan, who is responsible in the Union for promoting the sport,
said western athletes demonstrated an impressive performance at
the world championships last August in the United States.
</P>
<P>
"The Asians would face a tough challenge from them in three to
four years," he said. "We have but to take this challenge."
</P>
</TEXT>
