<HEADLINE> Indonesia to Build Coal Upgrading Facility </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian state-owned coal
mining company Pt Tambang Batubara Bukit Asam plans to build a
coal upgrading facility at its mining area in Tanjung Enim, South
Sumatra.
</P>
<P>
The up-grading plant will improve low-quality coal to make it
fit for various consumer purposes and exports, according to the
company's technical director Purba at a recent seminar on energy
demand.
</P>
<P>
The coal processed by the company, Budit Asam, which came from
surrounding regions, was of low quality since 69 percent of it
consisted of lignite coal, which has a low calorific value and
high water content, making it less popular for consumer usage.
</P>
<P>
Bukit Asam coal is currently used to operate power generators
in the region.
</P>
<P>
Bukit Asam's plans were made to anticipate increasing demand
for coal, both from the domestic and export markets.
</P>
<P>
The role of coal as a source of primary energy in Indonesia has
shown a steady increase, particularly for power generation.
</P>
