<HEADLINE> Duma's Resolutions May Lead to Confrontation: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The Communist-controlled State
Duma's denunciation on Friday of the 1991 agreements which
dissolved the Soviet Union mark "the first steps along the path
leading to confrontation of powers" an aide of President Boris
Yeltsin said today.
</P>
<P>
Dmitry Ryurikov, who is in charge of international affairs, told
a news briefing that the resolutions passed last Friday by the
Duma (the lower house of the Russian Parliament), which is
dominated by the Communist Party, was "a show of strength (by the
communists), although a very dubious strength."
</P>
<P>
He said the communists, who maintain the agreements were
unconstitutional, were trying to destabilize Russia and had
succeeded in creating "chaos and confused the picture in order to
facilitate their own grasp for power."
</P>
<P>
Ryurikov accused the sponsors of the Duma resolutions of trying
to disrupt integration among members of the Commonwealth of
Independent States at a time when negotiations are heading for a
breakthrough. Russia, Belarus and Kazakhstan have been holding
talks on deepening cooperation and possible integration.
</P>
<P>
He denied that Yeltsin, who as President signed the 1991
agreements, may use force in his struggle with the Duma, a
response to Communist Party leader Gennady Zyuganov's statement
earlier today that "there are hot heads in the president's
entourage who intend to ban the State Duma's activity."
</P>
<P>
Ryurikov said, "I know nothing about such consultations but, in
any case, it is not a method favoured by the president, and the
president will not agree to any forcible steps".
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin himself also issued a denial. "As you can see, nothing
has happened, let them not fear anything. Zyuganov will not need
an armored vehicle to get to his own office," Yeltsin told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
Zyuganov, 51, is seen here as the strongest rival for Yeltsin
in the presidential elections scheduled for June 16. 
</P>
</TEXT>
