<DOCNO> XIE19960318.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-18 16:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More U.S. Companies Buy Back Own Stocks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, March 18 (Xinhua) -- A record number of listed
companies on the New York stock market are planning to buy back
shares of their own stock.
</P>
<P>
The USA Today reported that so far this year, 293 companies
have said they will be repurchasing an estimated 38 billion U.S.
dollars of stock.
</P>
<P>
Repurchase announcements boost stock prices because they signal
a big buyer coming to support prices. "It is a sign of confidence
in the company" from insiders, says Richard Peterson, analyst at
Securities Data, which is tracking the trend.
</P>
<P>
The analyst predicted that 1996 will witness more than 1,200
announcements for more than 150 billion U.S. dollars of stock.
</P>
<P>
Buybacks got hot in 1994, with 1,012 announcements, up from 606
the year before. Then the stock market was going nowhere and
corporations could easily argue that their shares were bargains.
But as stock prices surge in 1995, buy-back plans kept coming,
with a record 1,108 announcements for 99 billion U.S. dollars of
stock.
</P>
<P>
History and logic say that the trend should stop when stocks
climb, according to economists, who now attribute the unexpected
buying spree to strong cash flows and pressure from shareholders
for higher stock prices.
</P>
<P>
In addition, dividends are taxed as ordinary income for
shareholders. Buybacks can produce capital gains, which are taxed
at lower rates.
</P>
<P>
Economists have argued on the buyback trend, trying to figure
out the best way for investment: whether to invest in stock or in
new factories, equipment and products.
</P>
<P>
Despite the fast increase of buyback announcements, the actual
buying was not as high as expected. Securities Data estimated that
companies carry out only a third of announced plans.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960318.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-18 16:35 </DATE_TIME>
