<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barings Case to Go to Tribunal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 18 (Xinhua) -- At least one of the nine former
Barings managers charged with misconduct by the Securities and
Futures Authority (SFA) is ready to refuse a settlement and take
his case to a tribunal to force the debate about the merchant
bank's collapse into the open.
</P>
<P>
The Financial Times reported today that the executive, who did
not wish to be named, said he was meeting his lawyers next week
and was prepared to contest the SFA's charges that he had failed
to act with "due skill, care and diligence" before the disaster.
</P>
<P>
The SFA, the regulator for brokers and futures dealers, which
has been investigating 12 former senior Barings employees, Friday
served notices of disciplinary proceedings against the nine former
executives of Barings.
</P>
<P>
The authority, which grants the vital licenses needed to
operate in Britain's financial markets, is suspending the
individuals from its registers for one to three years, and it has
charged them costs of 10,000 pounds (15,200 U.S. dollars) each.
</P>
<P>
The nine executives,including Peter Norris, the former chief
executive of Barings Investment Bank, and Ron Baker, the former
head of the financial products group, have 10 working days to come
to a settlement with the SFA, and a further 10 if they wish to
appeal.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
