<DOCNO> XIE19960318.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-18 16:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Five African Leaders Pledge to Ensure Refugees' Safe Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Five African presidents today
called on the international community to provide necessary funds
to ensure the refugees, most of them from Rwanda, to go home
safely, according to reports reaching from Tunis.
</P>
<P>
At the three-day Central Africa Summit which began Saturday in
the capital city of Tunisia, the presidents of Burundi, Rwanda and
neighboring Tanzania, Uganda and Zaire said they would launch a
new crackdown on extremists in the refugee camps.
</P>
<P>
In a joint statement, they pledged to shut down the arms flow
to all those perpetrating cross-border raids.
</P>
<P>
Rwanda's refugees fled after hardline Hutus killed up to 1
million minority Tutsis and allied Hutus in 1994.
</P>
<P>
A Tutsi-led government now runs Rwanda, and has urged all
exiled Rwandans to return.
</P>
<P>
Extremists in refugee camps in neighboring Burundi, Tanzania,
Uganda and Zaire have stirred fears that returnees risk jail,
torture or even death.
</P>
<P>
At the summit, the five African leaders, along with former
U.S. President George Bush, discussed the security measures that
will persuade 1.9 million Hutu refugees, most of them from Rwanda,
to return home in peace.
</P>
<P>
"The goal is for all refugees who are not guilty of genocide to
return to Rwanda," said Carter, who mediated the three-day talks.
</P>
<P>
He said that the removal of the intimidators will be another
major step forward, adding that the intimidators will be
identified and arrested.
</P>
<P>
The five African presidents also pledged to ease simmering
ethnic tensions in Burundi where more than 100,000 people have
died in violence since Tutsi soldiers murdered the Hutu president
in October 1993. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
