<HEADLINE> India's 3rd Force Launches Election Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The National Front-Left Front
(NF-LF) combine in India today virtually kicked off its election
campaign with a call to reject the hawala-tainted Indian National
Congress and Bharatiya Janata party (BJP), the Press Trust of
India said.
</P>
<P>
The hawala case refers to an 18-million-US-dollar bribery
scandal which involves many leading politicians in the country
including BJP President L.K. Advani and some cabinet ministers.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a rally in Patna, Bihar, senior leaders of the
parties stressed the need for evolving a third front to "combat
the forces of corruption and communalism" represented by the
ruling Congress Party and major opposition BJP.
</P>
<P>
In order to make the best use of the hawala scandal, parties of
the NF-LF combine have met repeatedly for the formation of a third
force.  Due to the lack of a prominent figure to lead the force
and some other differences among them, the parties have so far
failed to reach an agreement on the issue even as the general
elections are around the corner.
</P>
<P>
Janata Dal president Laloo Prasad, who also addressed the rally
today, put forward a proposal urging former prime minister V.P.
Singh to come out his "self-imposed political exile" and steer the
NF-LF combine to power in the coming elections.  
</P>
</TEXT>
