<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK to Secure a Defense Contract from UAE </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 18 (Xinhua) -- General Electric Co. (GEC),
Britain's leading defense contractor, is on the brink of securing
a multi-billion pound order to supply a set of new weapons systems
to the United Arab Emirates(UAE), according to a report in the
Times today.
</P>
<P>
The deal, believed to be worth up to five billion pounds
(roughly 7.5 billion US dollars) involves development of a new
"super-intelligent" missile similar to the American Tomahawk
cruise missile.
</P>
<P>
Secret negotiations on the contract have been under way for
more than a year, and the technology involved has been
exhaustively tested over recent months.
</P>
<P>
It was believed that the deal has taken so long to negotiate
because the UAE has in recent years loosened its dependence on
Britain as its prime supplier of armaments and has been trying to
cut defense procurement costs by encouraging competitions among
foreign manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, Britain has also been negotiating with the UAE
on a military treaty, similar to tie-ups being negotiated between
the Emirates and the US and France, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The treaty, probably in the form of a memorandum of
understanding, would cover deployment and stationing of British
troops in UAE.
</P>
<P>
Although it is not a trade agreement, the memorandum would form
a framework within which commercial negotiations could proceed.
</P>
<P>
GCE has long supplied its Hakim guided weapon system to the
UAE, and is said to be offering one of two possible upgraded
versions of this system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
