<HEADLINE> Kidnappers Rule Out Early Release of Hostages  in Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of the kidnappers group,
Free Papua Movement (OPM) in Irian Jaya, said they have no
immediate plan to free the 11 hostages they have held for more
than two months.
</P>
<P>
Kelly Kwalik and Daniel Kogoya confirmed this in a written
interview with the Indonesian popular daily "Kompas".  The
interview, dated March 2, only reached "Kompas" on March 16,
according to sources from local media here today.
</P>
<P>
"We will hold the hostages until there is a recognition by the
Indonesian government and the international community," said the
OPM leaders in the written interview.
</P>
<P>
OPM, an anti-government organization, has been fighting for an
independent state in Irian Jaya, the former Dutch colony, which
became the Indonesian province of Irian Jaya in 1964.
</P>
<P>
The demand had been flatly refused by the Indonesian
government.
</P>
<P>
OPM abducted 26 people including seven foreigners on January 8.
 Later, on separate occasions, OPM freed 15 hostages including one
Germany. There are still 11 hostages in the hands of OPM
including four Britons and two Dutch nationals.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian Armed Forces' spokesman Brigadier General Amir
Syarifudin said on March 17 in Surabaya that the Indonesian Armed
Forces intended to continue to use their "persuasive" approach in
getting the release of all hostages, said Antara report.  
</P>
</TEXT>
