<HEADLINE> China Continues Economic Links with Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, March 18 (Xinhua) -- China will continue to
energetically take part in Pakistan's economic progress by
extending as much technical assistance as possible, said Chinese
Ambassador to Pakistan Zhang Chengli.
</P>
<P>
"We will promote and encourage Chinese companies to have more
economic and trade cooperation of various forms with Pakistan," he
said at a seminar on future prospects of Sino-Pakistan relations
here today.
</P>
<P>
He said the Chinese government will give Chinese companies more
incentives to use supplier's credit for more projects and labor
cooperation in Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
The government, he said, will also undertake necessary efforts
to improve the quality of its export commodities and supervise
Chinese companies' performance.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that in future, Pakistan and China should
strengthen bilateral exchanges of various fields, especially the
high-level exchanges of visit.
</P>
<P>
He said major efforts should be devoted to enhance bilateral
economic and trade cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed the need to further strengthen consultation
and cooperation in international issues between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He also said that China will take measures to solve problems
existing in Sino-Pakistan economic and trade relations, especially
the imbalance of bilateral trade volume which is in China's favor.
</P>
<P>
"With joint efforts by the two countries, the problem of
imbalance will be gradually settled," he added.
</P>
<P>
Other speakers at the seminar, including former Chief of Army
Staff of Pakistan Aslam Beg, former Secretary General of Pakistan
Foreign Ministry and former Ambassador to China Ahmed Bhatty,
expressed their confidence that the time-tested and all weather
Sino-Pak relations would have a bright future.  
</P>
