<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-18 15:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Christopher Cautiously Optimistic over Test Ban Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, March 18 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State Warren
Christopher said here today that he was cautiously optimistic that
a comprehensive nuclear test ban treaty could be reached this year
in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
"I'm convinced that now we stand on the threshhold of being
able to realize and reach that important goal," Christopher told a
news conference after a series of meetings this morning which were
designed to push ahead the ongoing negotiations on the test ban
treaty.
</P>
<P>
Christopher, who came to Geneva Sunday, met representatives of
other four nuclear weapon states, namely Russia, China, France and
Britain, as well as representative of the Group 21 of the
non-aligned countries.
</P>
<P>
He told the reporters that he had called on the other nuclear
weapon states to take the lead to accelerate the negotiations and
synchronize their approaches to a test ban treaty.
</P>
<P>
Christopher said he had "good discussions" with Russia and
China Monday morning on one of the key outstanding issue, namely
the scope of a test ban treaty and the three "are drawing close
together" on the issue.
</P>
<P>
However, he also said he did not want to be overoptimistic.
"I'm not saying that either of the two countries or any of the
parties have given up positions they previously asserted," he
said.
</P>
<P>
On the scope issue, the United States support the Australian
proposal which suggest to ban "any nuclear weapon test explosion
or any other nuclear explosion". But China has proposed that the
peaceful nuclear explosions should be exempt from the test ban.
</P>
<P>
Later Monday morning, Christopher also met representatives from
Egypt, India, Indonesia, Mexico, Morocco and Pakistan of the Group
21.
</P>
<P>
He assured them that a comprehensive nuclear test ban treaty
will contribute to the nuclear disarmament goal and will help to
prevent the creation of new generation of nuclear weapons by
nuclear weapon states.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile Christopher also warned that linking the test ban
treaty to a fixed time table of nuclear disarmament, which is
demanded by the non-aligned countries, would be "non-productive"
and would jeopardize the ongoing test ban talks.
</P>
<P>
To push ahead the nuclear test ban talks is only one objective
of Christopher's Geneva trip. He would also meet three Balkan
leaders Monday afternoon to maintain pressure for implementation
of the Bosnian peace accords.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
