<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Adoption Official Explodes Orphan Mistreatment Myth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The recent report by the
U.S. Human Rights Watch alleging maltreatment in Chinese
orphanages "does not present an accurate picture," says Filis
M. Casey, executive director of the International Adoption Agency.
</P>
<P>
In a signed opinion published in the Washington Post on March
13, Casey described as "false" the implication that there is an
official policy in China allowing children to die through
inattention, as contained in a report entitled "American Parents
and Chinese Babies" published by Human Rights Watch on February 21.
</P>
<P>
Casey said she had visited many orphanages in China and had
"witnessed the substantial improvement in the physical facilities
and level of care provided because of the donations made to such
orphanages by those families adopting Chinese orphans or abandoned
children."
</P>
<P>
Chinese officials have discussed in depth their concerns for
children with special needs, she added.
</P>
<P>
"I can state that the reported mistreatment does not reflect
the experience of those of us involved in Chinese adoptions over
the past few years," Casey said.
</P>
<P>
The director went on to say that her experience only confirms
her belief that "the staff of these orphanages are committed to
providing a safe, healthy, loving environment to the extent
possible under difficult circumstances."
</P>
<P>
While acknowledging "there may have been neglect or abuse in
the past," Casey stressed: "we believe the current state of
commitment to care for the orphans or abandoned children in China
demonstrates a strong commitment by the Chinese government to the
care and protection of one of the most vulnerable segments of
society: children who are in need of families."
</P>
<P>
She called on people to encourage the efforts that have been
made during the past few years rather than "criticizing what may
have occurred in the not-so-recent past." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960318.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-18 15:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Hosts International Water Resources Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The conference is co-sponsored by the the UN Conference on
Human Settlements (Habitat 2), the Chinese Ministry of
Construction and the Beijing municipal government. Nearly 200
officials and experts from over 50 countries, over a dozen
departments of the UN, and the various Chinese ministries.
</P>
<P>
The conference will focus on urban water resources management,
water supply cost and financing, water demand management, control
of waste water and sustainable utilization of water.
</P>
<P>
Wally N'Dow, assistant secretary-general of Habitat 2, in a
written speech to the conference today, called water shortage
a global crisis. He said that "Water for Thirsty Cities" is the
theme of the World Water Day this year.
</P>
<P>
According to a report made by the World Bank in 1995, nowadays
some 80 countries, with 40 percent of the world's population, lack
water. Also, in developing countries one billion people do not
have access to clean water. It is estimated that the water demand
all over the world will double every 21 years. The UN official
urged joint action by all countries to combat the water
crisis.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Construction Minister Hou Jie briefed the attendants on
China's water-supply situation at the conference today.
</P>
<P>
He said that China is a developing country short of water
resources. The per capita water volume stands at only 2,440 cu
m, which is only one fourth of the world's per capita figure.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the minister added, rainfall is unbalanced in both
timing and location, and the insufficiency of water supply has become
an important constraint on economic development in Chinese cities.
</P>
<P>
However, the minister said, the Chinese government has all
along given top priority to water resources management and urban
water supply, and has made considerable progress in this respect.
</P>
<P>
At present, the daily water supply capacity in Chinese cities
has reached 182 million cu m, the country's annual water supply
volume has hit 45.9 billion cu m and the coverage rate of water
supply in cities tops 93 percent.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, China has established a complete system of
urban water supply management regulations and legislation, and
formulated detailed medium and long-term plans for urban water
supply development.
</P>
<P>
Besides, water conservation and utilization departments have
been set up from the central government down to localities.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that from 1990 to 1994 China's cities saved a
total of 9.8 billion cu m of water, saving annually an average of
nearly two billion cu m of water. The recycling rate for
industrial-use water increased from 45 percent in 1989 to 60
percent, giving a strong boost to the sustainable development of
the urban economy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960318.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-18 15:27 </DATE_TIME>
