<HEADLINE> Nepal's Ruling Party Determined to Save Coalition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Nepal's main ruling Nepali
Congress (NC) Party is determined to defeat a no-confidence motion
against the three-party coalition government under Sher Bahadur
Deuba in a special parliament session later this week.
</P>
<P>
A meeting of the NC parliamentary party held here today decided
to save the Deuba government while it is facing the no-confidence
challenge from the main opposition Communist Party of Nepal (UML).
</P>
<P>
The NC parliamentary party called on two other parties in the
ruling coalition, the National Democratic Party (RPP) and Nepal
Goodwill Party, to defeat the no-confidence motion unitedly.
</P>
<P>
The UML party last week registered the no-confidence motion at
the parliament secretariat and was expected to table the motion in
the special house session starting from Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
However, whether the three-party government would step down or
not depends on the second ruling party RPP as it holds 19 seats in
the 205-seat House of Representatives. The main ruling NC and the
main opposition UML party have 86 and 88 MPs respectively in the
House.
</P>
<P>
UML has requested support for its motion from RPP and offered
to form a RPP-UML coalition government led by RPP parliamentary
party leader Rokendra Bahadur Chand to replace the present NC-led
one.
</P>
<P>
But RPP, which holds the key to survival of the present
government, so far has not clarified its stance on the
no-confidence motion as its leaders were divided into two groups
with contrary views on the issue.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
