<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senior Chinese Military Leader Meets French Visitors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 18 (Xinhua) -- A senior Chinese military leader
said here today that no one should make irresponsible remarks
about Chinese military exercises.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Zhen, vice-chairman of the Central Military Commission,
said that the recent military exercises and the missile test
launches are regular drills, and they have demonstrated the
determination and capacity of the Chinese armed forces to
safeguard state sovereignty and territorial integrity.
</P>
<P>
Zhang made the remarks here this afternoon when meeting with a
French business delegation headed by Jeannou Lacaze, president of
the Universal Investment Group of Paris and former chief of staff
of the armed forces of France.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said that the fundamental reason for the present tense
situation in the Taiwan Straits lies in the activities of some
leaders of the Taiwan authorities who advocate "Taiwan
independence" and of some foreign forces who support this
conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that Taiwan is an integral part of China and the
issue of Taiwan is purely an internal affair of China.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has often reiterated its basic
principles of "peaceful reunification" and "one country, two
systems", he said.
</P>
<P>
China will never promise to abstain from resorting to arms on
the Taiwan issue, Zhang said, adding that such an eventuality
would only occur in the case of a declaration by Taiwan of
"independence" or invasion of Taiwan by foreign forces.
</P>
<P>
Lacaze said that France is very much concerned about China's
stand on the issue of Taiwan, and it believes each country in the
world has the right to safeguard its own interests.
</P>
<P>
And therefore, he said, France fully understands the importance
of a powerful and unified country, and fully understands that
China cannot turn a blind eye to what happens in Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting Zhang and the guests also exchanged views on
the promotion of cooperation between businesses of the two
countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
