<HEADLINE> India's Ruling Party to Go Alone in Polls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 18 (Xinhua) -- India's ruling Congress Party
said today that it would go alone in the coming general elections
except in Tamil Nadu where the alliance partner was yet to be
decided, the Press Trust of India said.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a rally in Himachal Pradesh, General Secretary of
All India Congress Committee (AICC) B.P. Maurya ruled out any
alliance between the Congress Party and other parties in Uttar
Pradesh and Bihar, two key states in the general elections.
</P>
<P>
He claimed that the Congress Party would win a comfortable
majority in the forthcoming elections.
</P>
<P>
The party had gained considerable grounds since the last
elections, he said, adding that the government's performance and
stability would be the main election plank of the party.
</P>
<P>
Though the dates for the general elections are yet to be
announced, parties in India have recently speeded up efforts to
seek allies at national and state levels.
</P>
<P>
The Congress Party is reportedly considering a tie-up with
AIADMK, the ruling party in Tamil Nadu. But Prime Minister P.V.
Narasimha Rao has not made a decision on the issue yet.  
</P>
