<HEADLINE> Military Govt To Hand Over To Civilian One in 14 Days </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The military government today
released two decrees, preparing to hand over to a civilian
government in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
The first decree states that the military government "will
hand over to the new head of state not later than 14 days after
the date on which that person is declared elected by the
returning officer."
</P>
<P>
Also today, supporters of Tejan Kabbah who is now the
president elect, paraded in the streets of the capital carrying
banners and making victory signs.
</P>
<P>
Kabbah, a moslem lawyer of the Sierra Leone People's Party got
59.49 percent of the vote on Friday, emerging victorious from the
runoff ballot.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the crowd in the capital, Kabbah, who worked for
many years for the U.N. Development Program in East Africa and
New York and is said to have diplomatic skills that could help in
negotiations with the rebels, thanked the paraders for supporting
him in the voting.
</P>
<P>
The second decree grants indemnity to members of the armed
forces and civilian secretary of state appointed by the military
government from April 1992.
</P>
<P>
No action or other legal proceeding, whether civil or
criminal, shall be instituted in any court of law or tribunal,
the decree added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the United Nations monitoring team which supervised
the March 15 presidential runoff said today that "the poll was
conducted in a procedurally correct manner."
</P>
<P>
"No irregularity or fraud was observed that would cast into
doubt the ultimate outcome of the vote," it said in a statement.
</P>
</TEXT>
