<DOCNO> XIE19960318.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-18 14:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Troops to Withdraw from Chechnya: Grachev </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Russian Defense Minister Pavel
Grachev today said Russian troops would start a gradual pullout
from Chechnya in April, but said Interior troops would remain.
</P>
<P>
"A gradual withdrawal of military units and formations, not
engaged in special operations, outside Chechnya will begin in
April as the president has promised," Grachev told reporters,
referring to a plan adopted by the Security Council last Friday.
</P>
<P>
But he said the army would continue to help Interior troops in
the rebel republic carry out special operations until the
remaining armed Chechen separatists are completely defeated.
</P>
<P>
Special operations will also be necessary to fight any new
criminal gangs which may emerge, he added.
</P>
<P>
Grachev said he supported a "complex approach" to the
Chechen settlement which includes both military and political
measures.
</P>
<P>
"The situation in Chechnya cannot be solved only by power
methods, there should be a combination of military, political and
socio-economic methods of the settlement," the military leader
pointed out.
</P>
<P>
He made it clear that had there not been peace talks with
Chechen separatists last summer under the orders of Prime Minister
Viktor Chernomyrdin, the conflict in Chechnya could have been
settled earlier.
</P>
<P>
The minister said he had foreseen the current situation back in
1995 and had warned that a suspension of fighting after the
hostage drama in Bubennovsk would have a negative impact on the
whole situation in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
In the summer of 1995, Russian troops temporarily suspended
hostilities after the separatists, under the command of Shamil
Basayev, raided Budennovsk in southern Russia and seized several
thousand hostages.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin has promised an end to the 15-month war in Chechnya
before the country's presidential elections scheduled for June 16.
</P>
<P>
Last Friday, the Security Council approved a Chechen settlement
plan. Yeltsin told reporters after the meeting that he would soon
address the nation to announce details of the plan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960318.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-18 14:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai PM's visit to Myanmar Marks Beginning of  New Chapter in Bilateral Ties: Joint Communique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Thai Prime Minister Banharn
Silpa-Archa's visit to Myanmar has marked "the beginning of a new
chapter in the bilateral relations of Myanmar and Thailand in
their efforts to further promote the friendly relations and
mutually beneficial cooperation between their two countries and
peoples."
</P>
<P>
This was contained in a joint communique issued here today at
the end of Banharn's two-day official visit to Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
The communique said that Thailand remains strongly committed to
that Thailand and Myanmar share a common destiny and that a
prosperous and secure Myanmar is vital for Thailand's own
stability and well-being.
</P>
<P>
The communique said that Myanmar steadfastly adhered to the
principles of peaceful co-existence and welcomed the opportunity
to consolidate and promote further the existing friendly relations
between the two neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
The communique stressed that both prime ministers reaffirmed
their determination to further strengthen all the existing
mechanisms for consultation between the two countries including
the Joint Commission, the Joint Boundary Committee and the
Regional Border Committee with a view to making them more
effective in enhancing cooperation and understanding between the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
The communique confirmed that Myanmar had reopened the two
border checkpoints, namely Tachilek-Maesai and Kawthaung-Ranong,
and the border checkpoint at Myawaddy-Maesot will be reopened on
March 19.
</P>
<P>
The communique stated that with a view to contributing further
the environment of peace and stability along the border, the two
prime ministers agreed that the Myanmar-Thailand Joint Boundary
Committee (JBC) shall, on the basis of the existing agreements,
survey and demarcate as soon as possible the entire boundary
except the sector already demarcated under the 1991 memorandum of
understanding relating to the fixed boundary on the Maesai-Namruak
rivers sector.
</P>
<P>
The agreement on border trade between Myanmar and Thailand,
which was signed on March 17, would help promote trade between the
two countries in a more systematic and orderly manner, the
communique said.
</P>
<P>
The communique also said the two prime ministers also agreed
that the second meeting of the Joint Working Group on border
crossing between the two countries would be held soonest with a
view to working out ways and means to synchronize the procedures
and practices on border crossing at respective border checkpoints.
</P>
<P>
The communique also disclosed that Myanmar will commute the
remaining term of sentence and release 100 Thai prisoners who are
presently serving prison terms in Myanmar in view of the existing
friendly relations between the two countries and in commemoration
of the 50th anniversary of King Bhumibol Adulyadej's accession to
the throne.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
