<HEADLINE> South Korea, Egypt Agree to Promote Trade, Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, March 18 (Xinhua) -- South Korea and Egypt agreed here
today to boost bilateral trade and investment to two billion
U.S. dollars over the next three years.
</P>
<P>
The agreement came after talks between South Korean Foreign
Minister Gong Ro-myung and his Egyptian counterpart, Amr Moussa,
the Foreign Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Trade between the two countries stood at 585 million dollars
last year. South Korea had a trade surplus with Egypt, with
exports of 470 million dollars and imports of 115 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Gong and Moussa also agreed to enhance cooperation in
anti-terrorism and other fields in the United Nations Security
Council (UNSC). Both South Korea and Egypt are non-permanent
standing members of the UNSC.
</P>
<P>
The two foreign ministers said they were satisfied with the
progress of bilateral relations since diplomatic ties between the
two countries were set up in April 1995.
</P>
<P>
They vowed to support each other's bid for membership of the
sub-commission on the prevention of discrimination and protection
of minorities, which is affiliated to the United Nations
Commission on Human Rights.
</P>
<P>
Gong and Moussa also inked an accord on mutual exemption of
visas for diplomats and officials and a memorandum of
understanding on the establishment of a high-level policy
consultation forum. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
