<HEADLINE> China to Become Postal Services Giant by 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 18 (Xinhua) -- China is expected to provide 30
billion yuan-worth of postal services by the turn of this century,
with the annual growth rate reaching 21.6 percent during the
1996-2000 period.
</P>
<P>
This was revealed by Liu Pingyuan, vice-minister of posts and
telecommunications, at a news conference held here today
to mark the 100th anniversary of the birth of the country's postal
services, which will fall on March 20.
</P>
<P>
China aims to become a postal giant by the end of the year 2000,
with the volume of its postal matter ranking among the world's top
ten, said Liu Pingyuan.
</P>
<P>
Last year China provided a total of 11.27 billion yuan-worth of
postal services, up 17 percent over 1994.
</P>
<P>
China added 18,884 km of postal routes last year, including 99
inner-province trunks, bringing the country's national total
length of postal trunk routes to 1.886 million km. More than 2,300
post offices and bureaus were built last year, bringing the total
to 62,883.
</P>
<P>
Now China has mail exchange services with more than 140
countries and regions, and postal remittance exchanges with a
dozen countries. In addition, there is EMS service between China
and more than 200 countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
China is expected to handle a total of 43 billion postal
items by 2000, and 83.5 billion by 2010.
</P>
<P>
During the coming five years China will set up 255 postal
centers, install computer systems in 18.5 percent of post offices
and connect 15.15 percent of postal savings branches with the
national postal savings network. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
