<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-18 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Opens Annual Human Rights Session </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Commission on
Human Rights opened its 52nd session here Monday morning to
discuss the human rights situation throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
The six-week meeting will focus on 28 topics on civil,
political, economic, social and cultural rights.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Boutros Boutros-Ghali underscored the
importance of the right to development at the opening ceremony.
</P>
<P>
There is an "essential link between the protection of human
rights and the imperative of development," he said and emphasized
the link between human rights and peace and democracy.
</P>
<P>
"The rights of the human person will be guaranteed first and
foremost by restoring peace," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I am convinced that the process of democratization is
inseparable from the protection of human rights", he said, adding,
however, that "we are not urging States to engage in some sort of
mimicry or to borrow political forms that come from elsewhere."
</P>
<P>
Ambassador Gilberto Vergne Saboia from Brazil was elected
president of the 52nd session at today's meeting.
</P>
<P>
Besides the 53 member states of the commission that have a
vote, other non-voting countries and non-governmental
organizations are also at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Commission on Human Rights, set up in February 1946, is one
of the seven sub-commissions under the U.N. Economic and Social
Council. It convenes a six-week session every year and its
members, selected on a geographical basis, have a tenure of three
years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
