<HEADLINE> Trial of Two Former S. Korean Presidents Resumes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The second session on the mutiny
and treason charges involving former South Korean Presidents
Chun Doo-hwan and Roh Tae-woo was held at the Seoul District
Court here today.
</P>
<P>
At the trial, prosecutors charged that Chun and Roh as well as
their cronies mobilized troops to arrest then Army Chief of Staff
Chung Sung-hwan and several other loyal generals without an
presidential permit with the intention to control the armed forces
on the evening of December 12, 1979.
</P>
<P>
Also standing trial at the same court were 11 close aides of
the two ex-presidents, who played key roles in the military mutiny
on December 12, 1979, which was led by Chun and Roh.
</P>
<P>
However, Chun claimed that he and his colleagues had to mobilize
troops because some army generals made rebellious acts first.
</P>
<P>
He contended that Major General Chang Tae-wan ordered his men
to kill him and shell the Kyongbok Palace area of Seoul
indiscriminately to "jeopardize national security."
</P>
<P>
The prosecution today questioned Chun and two of his coup
colleagues, Yoo Hak-seong, then deputy defense minister for
logistics, and Hwang Young-si, first corps commander. Roh Tae-woo
was questioned at the first trial session on March 11.
</P>
<P>
Chun, who loomed large as the Army strongman after the 1979
military mutiny, seized power on August 27, 1980, and ruled the
nation until February 1988. He was followed by Roh who stepped
down in February 1993.
</P>
<P>
Chun and Roh, who were arrested last year, have been indicted
for mutiny and treason, in addition to graft charges.
</P>
<P>
The third session on the trial of Chun and Roh will be held
on March 25. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
