<DOCNO> XIE19960318.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-18 13:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Peace in Kwazulu/Natal, a Long Way to Go </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Prospects for convening a
long-planned peace gathering among Zulus named Imbizo in
Kwazulu/Natal Province is becoming increasingly elusive when a
top-level pre-Imbizo meeting of traditional leaders (Amakhosi)
failed last week.
</P>
<P>
The planned Imbizo, proposed by President Nelson Mandela
earlier this year, was widely considered as an urgent step to
bring an end to the unabated political violence in strife-torn
Kwazulu/Natal.
</P>
<P>
The meeting of Amakhosi on Friday, which was supposed to set
the date and scene for the planned Imbizo, failed to reach any
agreement on the matter.
</P>
<P>
Instead, the five-hour meeting, attended by Mandela, Zulu King
Goodwill Zwelithini and Inkatha Freedom Party (IFP) leader
Mangosuthu Buthelezi, was marked by heated acrimonious exchange,
interjections and jeers by some chiefs, especially when Mandela
told them not to raise Buthelezi above the King.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the president, who had earlier taken a
conciliatory stance, lashed out at the chiefs. He later took a
harder line, telling the apparently hostile hecklers: "You can
shout until you are blue in the face, but I am going to lay down
the riot act for everybody in this country if you are killing
innocent people."
</P>
<P>
Mandela further claimed that dark and sinister forces were at
work in Kwazulu/Natal fuelling violence between the African
National Congress (ANC) and the IFP.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that more than 20,000 people had been killed
in the province since fighting broke out between the two black
rival organizations in the mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
However, several speakers, including Buthelezi, raised a
number of issues that were stumbling blocks to an Imbizo,
claiming the Zulu nation is being mistreated by the government.
</P>
<P>
They complained that the government has ignored their demands
for a self-governing Zulu kingdom and for international mediation
over the constitution.
</P>
<P>
In his speech at the meeting, Buthelezi protested that the
National government was on the verge of taking away "the
ancestral land of the Zulu nation" and that King Zwelithini would
no longer be the trustee of land on behalf of chiefs.
</P>
<P>
Buthelezi also complained that Zwelithini was no longer
leading the Zulus in their struggle to attain a Zulu kingdom.
</P>
<P>
"How can we go into an Imbizo to promote peace and unity when
echoes of accusations and counter-accusations of murder and
general mayhem reverberate every day?" he asked.
</P>
<P>
Although the meeting was a failure in whichever way one looks
at it, Mandela was still optimistic about the prospects of the
holding of the planned Imbizo, saying he was not discouraged by
the outcome of Friday's meeting of Amakhosi.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters in Pretoria on Saturday, Mandela said:
"I don't get discouraged when we meet obstacles. The overwhelming
majority of people in Kwazulu/Natal are for peace. I fully
believe we will be able to sort out this matter and that we will
have an Imbizo."
</P>
<P>
It is also reported that Mandela will make another bid this
week to revive the peace initiative in Kwazulu/Natal.
</P>
<P>
Mandela's director of communications Joel Netshitenzhe said on
Sunday the President would consult various role-players and that
a date for a follow-up meeting would be set during the course of
this week.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, no matter what the peace Imbizo might lead to in
the future, Friday's meeting of Amakhosi suggests the ANC and
IFP, the chiefs and the government, Mandela and Buthelezi, are
still far apart as they ever were.
</P>
<P>
This does not augur well for Kwazulu/Natal, because
deep-rooted political differences between the ANC and IFP cannot
be uprooted by a mere peace gathering, Observers here say.
</P>
<P>
Peace in Kwazulu/natal remains a long way to go. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960318.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-18 13:03 </DATE_TIME>
