<HEADLINE> China's Domestic Satellite Telecom Network Taking Shape </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 18 (Xinhua) -- A domestic satellite
telecommunications network covering 20 cities in China has taken
shape, after the country built 12 and expanded 21 satellite earth
stations.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the country has made a breakthrough in satellite
communications from analog technology to digital technology,
according to the Ministry of Posts and Telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
During the Eighth Five-Year Plan period (1991-1995) China
built or expanded satellite earth stations in Beijing, Chongqing,
Guangzhou, Xi'an, Kunming, Lanzhou, Hohhot, Urumqi, Haikou and
Lhasa.
</P>
<P>
In 1990 the ministry decided to put a total investment of 620
million yuan (about 75 million US dollars) into constructing a
domestic satellite digital telecommunications network.
</P>
<P>
In the first phase the ministry constructed seven and expanded
seven satellite earth stations, while in the second phase it
constructed five and expanded 14.
</P>
<P>
Following five years of construction China has considerably
expanded the capacity of the long-distance telephone service,
especially in remote areas such as the Tibet Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The present domestic satellite digital telecommunications
network is now capable of carrying voice, picture and data
traffic, whereas the old network could only carry voice traffic.
</P>
<P>
In the Ninth-Five Year Plan period (1996-2000) the ministry
intends to make special efforts to complete a satellite digital
telecommunications network with a large capacity and high speed
covering all provincial capitals and medium-sized cities in
economically-developed areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
