<DOCNO> XIE19960318.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-18 12:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Grand Buddhist Rite Held in Beijing Lamasery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The most important Buddhist
lamasery in the Chinese capital ushered in the holiest day of the
year when lamas performed a traditional dance supposed to vanquish
demons and monsters here this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
That was the climax of an annual week-long grand Buddhist rite
held in the Yonghe Lamasery, the largest and best preserved
lamasery outside the Tibet Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The rite, held from the 23rd day of the first month to the
first day of the second month by the lunar calendar (March 12-19
this year) is held for the prosperity of the country and a happy
life for the people.
</P>
<P>
The lamasery, first built in 1694, used to be the residence of
Emperor Qianlong of the Qing Dynasty (1644-1911) before his
enthronement. It became the administrative center for lamaism by
the dynasty in 1744.
</P>
<P>
The sixth, ninth and tenth Panchen Lamas and the 13th and 14th
Dalai Lamas lectured or received worship from both lamas and
laymen here.
</P>
<P>
Covering an area of 66,000 sq m, the lamasery has now more than
80 Tibetan and Mongolian lamas, who hold Buddhist rites every
day. It receives over one million tourists every year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
