<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-18 12:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mandela, Winnie In Court For Divorce </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 18 (Xinhua) -- President Nelson Mandela
and his estranged wife Winnie Madizikela-Mandela, arrived at
Johannesburg's Rand Supreme Court this morning for the start of
their divorce proceedings.
</P>
<P>
Mandela is represented by human rights advocate Wim Trengove
while Winnie is by advocate Ishmael Semenya during the divorce
settlement.
</P>
<P>
Mrs. Mandela's lawyer Semenya asked for a postponement on the
grounds not all reconciliation attempts had been made, saying
customary law provisions had not been utilized.
</P>
<P>
However, Mandela's attorney Trengove told the court a
postponement should not be granted in the divorce proceedings
against Winnie because reconciliation was not possible between
them.
</P>
<P>
Trengove told the court that reports of Mrs. Mandela's "brazen
infidelity" had never been explained.
</P>
<P>
In response to the customary law aspect, Trengove said Mr.
Mandela's relative, chief paramount Kaizer Matanzima, who would
be expected to negotiate a reconciliation, was basically a
"sell-out who only gained power during apartheid."
</P>
<P>
Trengove said it would be unethical for the chief to mediate
in reconciliation attempts because at one time he had tried to
compete for Mrs. Mandela's affections. He lost to Mandela.
</P>
<P>
Both the president and his wife sat stern-faced and did not
look at each other for the first part of the legal proceedings to
end their 38-year marriage.
</P>
<P>
In an affidavit before the court, Mr. Mandela said he
respected customary law but viewed his marriage as being "on
paper only."
</P>
<P>
The president said he knew of no custom that dealt with the
dissolution of marriage.
</P>
<P>
Mandela, 78, who initiated divorce proceedings, married Winnie
Madizikela in 1958. The couple separated in 1992, two years after
Mandela's release from 27 years's imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
A legal source said money would be the central issue in the
divorce settlement.
</P>
<P>
Winnie was reportedly claiming half of her husband's estate,
worth an estimated 40 million Rand (about 11 million US Dollars).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
