<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-18 11:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Somali Factions Welcome UN Concern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Somali faction leaders, Ali
Mahdi Mohamed and Osman Hassan Ali Atto, have welcomed the U. N.
Security Council concern over the humanitarian situation in
Somalia.
</P>
<P>
A press statement issued by the Somali Salvation Alliance
(SSA) led by north Mogadishu faction leader Ali Mahdi Mohamed,
said the alliance welcomes "the keen interest that U.N. always
shows" to monitor the situation in Somalia.
</P>
<P>
The SSA also said they will cooperate with all genuine efforts
which the international community may undertake to help the
Somali community.
</P>
<P>
they further said they welcome the UN initiative to send to
Somalia a fact-finding mission to ascertain about the reasons
behind the renewed deterioration of the humanitarian condition.
</P>
<P>
The SSA argued that all Somali factions have an equal share of
responsibility in perpetuating the current ordeals of Somalia.
"the responsibility of the political and humanitarian instability
in Somalia lies on the shoulders of some handful anti-peace
elements," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
The SSA doesn't believe that any military solution could be
possible to settle the protracted political crises.
</P>
<P>
It also said they don't agree with the attitude of
generalizing with the notion of general culpability with regard
to responsibility of the past failures.
</P>
<P>
In the statement, the SSA also said they have never attempted
to make a self proclamation exercise as done by General Mohamed
Farah Aidid, another main faction in the country.
</P>
<P>
However, the statement of the SSA itself was issued from an
office called the Office of the President of Somali Republic
referring to Mr Ali Mahdi Mohamed.
</P>
<P>
Both radio north and south Mogadishu reiterate the presidency
of their owners, Ali Mahdi and General Aidid respectively.
</P>
<P>
On Friday or March 15, the UN Security Council have expressed
its concern over the worsening humanitarian situation is Somalia.
It said diseases and malnutrition are increasing in Somalia with
the lack of healthy political settlement.
</P>
<P>
They blamed the Somali factions for their failure of
reconciling among themselves. The security council attributed the
worsening humanitarian situation mainly to the continuing closure
of Mogadishu seaport.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the spokesman of General Aidid's
government, Mr Mohamed Qanyeare Afrah, said today his government
is welcoming any humanitarian assistance to Somalia and ready to
cooperate with the relief agencies.
</P>
<P>
However, Mr Afrah, the Interior Minister of General Aidid's
government, said his administration doesn't accept food messed up
with politics, saying, "we don't accept anybody to meddle in our
internal affairs."
</P>
<P>
He said his faction is not responsible for the worsening
humanitarian situation in Somalia, noting, "we're not those who
closed both the air and sea ports in Mogadishu."
</P>
<P>
Mogadishu seaport was closed last October after Ali Mahdi
Mohamed and Osman Hassan Ali Atto accused Sombana and Somali
Fruit, Banana Exporting Companies, of providing financial
assistance to their rival General Aidid.
</P>
<P>
However, some natural seaports including Merca, 100 km south
of Mogadishu and El-Ma'an, 30 km north of the capital, remain in
use by the merchants. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
