<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-18 11:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnamese Newspaper Criticizes U.S. Bill against Cuba </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Helms-burton Bill against
Cuba is an "insolent bill defying morality and the fundamental
principles of international laws and runs counter to the trend of
free trade and cooperation for common development, a Vietnamese
leading newspaper said today.
</P>
<P>
The "Nhan Dan" (people) newspaper said in a commentary that the
U.S. bill aimed to tighten economic sanctions against Cuba is in
fact an attempt to internationalize the economic and trade embargo
against Cuba.
</P>
<P>
The anti-Cuba bill had been adopted by the U.S. congress
following two U.S. airplanes were shut down by Cuba air force last
month. Havana accused Washington of violating Cuba's air space.
</P>
<P>
"The bill is typical of Washington's policy of placing its laws
above international law, giving itself the right to interfere
while ignoring a country's sovereignty and the right of
self-determination," the commentary said.
</P>
<P>
The approval of this bill by the U.S. government is a dangerous
precedent in international relations because it challenges not
only one country but also the world as a whole, the commentary
added.
</P>
<P>
It noted that far before it became law, the Helms-burton bill
imposing trade embargo on Cuba 35 years ago had stirred up a wave
of protest in the international community.
</P>
<P>
Latin America, the Caribbean countries as well as Russia, China
and even U.S. allies Canada and 15 European Union countries all
considered the passing of this bill a serious mistake unacceptable
in current time, the commentary said.
</P>
<P>
Although the United Nations' general assembly passed four
resolutions condemning the U.S. and requesting it to stop its
blockade against Cuba, the extreme right wing in the U.S. is still
pursuing its hostile policy, Nhan Dan noted.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper called on the United States to immediately put an
end to its "outmoded hostile policy against Cuba". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
