<DOCNO> XIE19960318.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-18 11:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tourist Arrivals to China on Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The number of overseas tourists
heading for the China mainland was over 3.85 million people in
January.
</P>
<P>
They generated foreign exchange income of over 600 million US
dollars for China.
</P>
<P>
Japanese tourists topped the list, followed by holiday makers
from South Korea. But the number of people heading east from
America and Europe was also up.
</P>
<P>
China National Tourism Administration reported in Beijing today
that January of 1996 saw a continued growth in momentum for
China's tourist industry.
</P>
<P>
There was an upturn trend in almost all the indicators, the
latest statistics show.
</P>
<P>
Though it fell within a slack season, January represented a 8.3
percent increase in overseas tourist arrivals to China, which
topped over 3.85 million.
</P>
<P>
Among them, were 446,300 foreign tourists, up 29.7 percent;
over 3.28 million guests from Hong Kong and Macao, up 5.6 percent;
118,100 Taiwan tourists, a rise of 20.3 percent; and 10,009
tourists of Chinese descent from all parts of the world, a growth
of 5.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
The major source markets of Asia, Europe and America, and
Oceania respectively rose by over 20 percent, 30 percent and 18
percent.
</P>
<P>
Among the 15 largest source countries most sent more tourists
to China in January.
</P>
<P>
Arrivals from Japan, the largest source country, reached
99,900, a jump of 59.9 percent; that from South Korea, the second
largest, hit 44,700, a soar of 65.9 percent; and that from the US
amounted to 37,900, up 27.7 percent. Arrivals from Canada, the
ninth largest source country, also recorded an impressive 53.7
percent growth, reaching 12,300.
</P>
<P>
In the same period, the country generated 692 million US
dollars of tourism foreign exchange earnings, up 19.8 percent over
the same period of last year. Among the total, 599 million US
dollars was spent by tourists who spent short spells in China,
accounting for 86.6 percent; and 93 million US dollars spent by
day trippers, accounting for 13.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to World Tourism Organization, China ranked the
fourth in tourist arrivals in 1995, as compared with the fifth in
1994. Tourist foreign exchange earnings ranking of China rose to
ninth place in 1995, from the tenth in 1994.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
