<HEADLINE> More Smuggling Cases Found in Vietnam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The Vietnamese Customs discovered
11,412 smuggling cases last year, accounting for 60 percent of the
total number detected in two years.
</P>
<P>
The figure was disclosed at a two-day Customs meeting held in
Ho Chi Minh City last week, which reviewed the enforcement of the
anti-smuggling laws promulgated two years ago, Vietnam News Agency
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The confiscated goods and lost Customs duties totalled 189.1
billion Vietnamese Dong (roughly 17.17 million U.S. dollars) in
terms of value.
</P>
<P>
Customs officers intercepted 1,800 antique items, more than
2,400 pornographic and reactionary publications, 16,800 assorted
tapes and discs, eight guns, 122 kg of explosive substances and
1,811 poison sprayers.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Customs also seized 30 kg of opium, 1.44 kg of
heroin and 20 kg of hashish, according to the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
