<HEADLINE> Iranian Extremists Stage Demonstration against Germany </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Some 200 Iranian extremists today
staged a demonstration in front of the German embassy here to
protest over a warrant issued by German Federal Prosecutor's
Office for arresting Iranian Information Minister Ali Fallahiyan.
</P>
<P>
Holding large black and white photos of blind-folded American
hostages, Ansar-e Hezbollah, a riotous and frightening group in
Iran, burnt U.S. and Israeli national flags in front of the German
embassy to condemn actions of "the pro-Zionist lobby" in Germany.
</P>
<P>
The extremist group held frequent demonstrations in Tehran
University, mosques and other public places in the past
months. They are often responsible for burning down book shops and
 making disturbances in universities.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrators from the group chanted slogans of "Europe
Beware," "Denounce U.S.A.," "Down with U.S.A." and "Down with
Israel." Loudspeakers placed on the back of a pickup truck
carried the voice of a boy directed to the embassy staff.
</P>
<P>
In a letter addressed to the German ambassador to Tehran,
the demonstrators demanded an apology for insulting "a sitting
minister" in the cabinet of President Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani.
</P>
<P>
The letter demanded that the warrant for Fallahiyan's arrest
should be canceled, and called on the German government to be
alert against U.S. and Israeli influences.
</P>
<P>
"We want a relationship based on mutual respect. If that
is achieved, the Moslems do not see any necessity to chant
Death to Germany in addition to Death to America and Death
to Israel," said the letter.
</P>
<P>
Some of the staff at the German embassy gathered behind
the windows to listen to the text of the letter. Some 100
policemen guarded the embassy
</P>
<P>
The letter criticized those Moslem politicians who thought that
Germany was a friend of Moslems. It further appealed to Iranian
Supreme Leader Ali Khamenei to announce "full alert to all the
Hizbollah members around the world to safeguard the honor and
dignity of Islam."
</P>
<P>
"We the Moslems do not have anything to lose in the world and
we would be gladly prepared to give up our lives in order to
safeguard Islam," it added.
</P>
<P>
The arrest warrant has been issued by German Federal
Prosecutor's Office for the Iranian information minister, charging
him with ordering the killing of four members of the Iranian
Kurdish opposition in Germany in 1992.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, Iran's parliament Speaker Ali Akbar Nateq-Nouri
termed as a grave mistake and unacceptable the verdict issued by
the German Federal Prosecutor against the Iranian information
minister.
</P>
<P>
The speaker stated that the German judicial system is an
independent power and that the verdict has no effect on the
existing relations between Tehran and Bonn.
</P>
<P>
Iran's Foreign Ministry deplored the arrest warrant, saying
that the case against Fallahiyan was not the least corroborated by
evidence.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of Iran's Foreign Ministry said "there was
absolutely no evidence on file pending in the said court that
adduced to the Iranian officials having been involved in its
subject-matter."
</P>
<P>
After four members of Iran's Kurdish opposition were found
murdered in a Berlin restaurant in 1992, the relations between
Iran and Germany has gone through periodic crises. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
