<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Balkan FMs' Meeting Significant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The meeting of foreign ministers of
Bulgaria, Greece and Romania in the Bulgarian Black Sea city of
Varna is of important significance for the Balkan region, said
Bulgarian Prime Minister Zhan Videnov today.
</P>
<P>
The meeting in Varna showed the criteria of mutual relationship
in Europe have flowered among some Balkan people, Videnov told
reporters after meeting with the foreign ministers of the three
countries.
</P>
<P>
Opportunities are open to other Balkan countries to get close
to or ally with the three countries, said the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
The tripartite meeting, which started Saturday afternoon and
ended Sunday evening, was focused on economic cooperation in
general and cooperation in infrastructure and telecommunications
projects between the three countries.
</P>
<P>
These included a second bridge over the Danube river, which
separates Bulgaria and Romania, and the project of an oil pipeline
linking Bulgaria and Greece.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria and Greece at the meeting expressed interest in
creating an integrated Balkan telephone network, an idea applauded
by Serbia. For this, the post ministers of the three countries
will meet in a few days.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers of Bulgaria, Greece and Romania agreed to
meet again in Bulgaria's capital in June this year, saying their
meeting will be helpful to developing regional cooperation in
Europe.
</P>
<P>
The first foreign ministers' meeting of the three countries
took place last August in Greece, when it was agreed that
periodical meetings would be held, open to the foreign ministers
of other Balkan countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
