<DOCNO> XIE19960318.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-18 09:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manufacturing Makes up One Third of Malaysia's GDP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's manufacturing
sector accounted for 33.1 percent of its gross domestic product
(GDP) in 1995, International Trade and Industry Minister Rafidah
Aziz said today.
</P>
<P>
After launching the country's "Industry Excellence Award 1996"
at her ministry, Rafidah said the figure represented an increase
of 1.5 percentage points over 1994.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, sales of manufactured products
totaled 159.189 billion Malaysian ringgit (about 63.67 billion US
dollars) in 1995, up 22.6 percent from 129.799 billion ringgit
(about 51.92 billion US dollars) in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Rafidah stressed that the good performance of the industry is
due not only to government policies but also, more importantly, to
the awareness of the industry itself.
</P>
<P>
On the "Industry Excellence Award," Rafidah said this year's
emphasis was on both promoting understanding of the requirement
for performance excellence and the need to share information on
the successful business or performance strategies.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, there is also a special award to
encourage manufacturers to reduce imported content in their
products.
</P>
<P>
With Malaysia's trade deficit standing at 9.2 billion ringgit
(about 3.68 billion US dollars) in 1995, Prime Minister Mahathir
Mohamad earlier asked local manufacturers to cut imports and
increase exports.  
</P>
</TEXT>
