<HEADLINE> Zamiba's City Councils Urged To Sell Houses At Affordable Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Zambian President Frederick
Chiluba has urged city councils in the country to sell government
houses at affordable prices to sitting tenants, "Zambia Daily
Mail" reported today.
</P>
<P>
President Chiluba made the call during his inspection of
council properties in northern city of Ndola yesterday.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba regretted that the civic authorities had set
exploitative prices on government houses being offered for sale
to residents.
</P>
<P>
He said councils had failed to sell their houses because they
were overpriced beyond the means of most of the sitting tenants.
</P>
<P>
"Let the people own their houses is part of a government
exercise to empower the people," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
He said the civic authorities should start tapping new sources
of revenue to sustain their operations after the sale of houses.
</P>
<P>
At present, collection of government house rents is one of
major sources of councils' income to support their operations.
</P>
<P>
To sell government houses to sitting tenants is part of the
government reform policy on housing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
