<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-18 09:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Further Eases Closure on Gaza, West Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli army today further
eased a three-week closure imposed on the Gaza Strip and the West
Bank following a series of suicide bombing attacks in Israel
earlier this month, which left more than 60 dead and over 150
wounded.
</P>
<P>
According to an Israel Radio report, basic medical supplies
will be transferred from Israel to Gaza, and flowers will be moved
from Gaza to Israel for packaging.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the number of Palestinian workers from the Gaza
Strip employed in the Erez industrial zone will also be increased.
</P>
<P>
Over the weekend, Israel eased aspects of the closure as
foodstuffs had been allowed into the Gaza trip, and Palestinians
have been permitted to move freely inside the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, about 500 Palestinian workers from Gaza, for the
first time in more than three weeks, were allowed to go back to
their jobs in the Erez industrial zone.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio said that Palestinian goods would also be able to
proceeded under Israeli army's escort from Gaza to the Ashkelon
port for export.
</P>
<P>
A decision will be made in the coming days on whether to permit
the transfer of goods by Palestinians from the Gaza Strip into
Israel, the report added.
</P>
<P>
However, a senior Israeli security source said Israel would
consider its stand on the closure only after Yasser Arafat, the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) president, arrests those
responsible for terrorist attacks in Israel.
</P>
<P>
He added that Israel would continue exerting pressure on
Arafat in order to arrest Mohammed Dief Baith and Hassan
Suleiman, both activists of the Hamas military wing Izzadin
Kassam.
</P>
<P>
In the wake of the closure, Israeli Prime Minister Shimon
Peres Sunday proposed a 100-million-U.S. dollar international fund
to create jobs for the Palestinians in the West Bank and the Gaza
Strip.
</P>
<P>
Peres told the weekly cabinet meeting of the Israeli
government that the closure would continue indefinitely because
Arafat and the PNA have not yet done enough to combat terror.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, he said, Israel's planned pullback from the West
Bank town of Hebron on March 28 would be delayed indefinitely
until the PNA catches all top Hamas fugitives on the list given to
them by Israel.
</P>
<P>
Apart from continuing the closure, Peres also said that he
favors deporting Palestinians linked to suicide bombers and will
continue blowing up the houses of families of suicide bombers.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israeli High Court has been asked to allow
Palestinian medical personnel to go back to their jobs in
hospitals in east Jerusalem from the sealed off areas.
</P>
<P>
The petition, submitted by various human rights groups, noted
that three hospitals in east Jerusalem have virtually shut down
because the doctors are unable to cross in due to the closure.
</P>
<P>
The PNA estimates losses from the closure, which has barred
more than 40,000 Palestinian workers from entering Israel, at 2 to
3 million U.S. dollars a day from salaries alone, and about the
same in terms of trade.
</P>
<P>
According to a Palestinian Radio report, the joint liaison
committee of donor states will meet twice in Gaza this week to
put together a 40-million-U.S.-dollar employment-generating
program so that Palestinians can weather what is expected to be a
long closure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
