<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heavy Industrial Center Boosting Agriculture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Liaoning, one of China's heavy
industrial centers, has pledged to apply science in the
development of agriculture.
</P>
<P>
It plans to form seven industrial setups, ranging from grain,
vegetables, fruit, animal husbandry, aquatic production and forest
and local and special products, to export-oriented agriculture, by
the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Social services in pre-farming supply, agro-techniques and
marketing, are expected to cover 80 percent of the rural areas.
</P>
<P>
At least one half of the farm, animal and aquatic products will
be turned into processed goods by the end of this century.
</P>
<P>
To accomplish the plan, the province will build 100
processing-transport-marketing enterprises, and 200 farm
production bases.
</P>
<P>
More households and villages will be encouraged to specialize
in certain crop cultivation and livestock breeding.
</P>
<P>
Xu Wencai, deputy governor of the province, said that Liaoning
is a province, with an urban population exceeding its rural
population in size. But, it is now self-sufficient in grain and
non-staple food.  
</P>
</TEXT>
