<HEADLINE> Uganda Oppositions Attack Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The National Inter-party
Cooperation (IPC) campaign team today accused the government of
planting its cadres and supporters to disrupt president hopeful
Paul Ssemogrerere's preparation for the presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued here, the IPC said the Uganda government
should immediately arrest and prosecute its supporters
terrorizing members of the IPC campaign teams throughout the
country.
</P>
<P>
The IPC is composed of the Democratic Party, the Uganda
People's Congress and the federal supporters.
</P>
<P>
It is the government obligation to provide maximum security to
all citizens of this country, it added.
</P>
<P>
The IPC was reacting to last Saturday's violent incident in
which members of the IPC campaign team were attacked and beaten
by a group of people in Fort Portal town, southwestern Uganda.
</P>
<P>
The mob stormed the IPC's consultative meeting at their
offices on Kiboga road and pelted them with rotten tomatoes, eggs
and stones.
</P>
<P>
The situation was saved after police came to intervene.
</P>
<P>
The IPC doubted whether the government has the capacity and
commitment to ensure safe, free and fair elections in Uganda,
said the statement. 
</P>
