<HEADLINE> Galindo Leads Qualifying Round at Figure Skating Worlds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
EDMONTON, Canada, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Rudy Galindo of the
United States and Japanese teenager Takeshi Honda won the men's
singles qualifying rounds on the opening day of the World Figure
Skating Championships here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Galindo, 26, was judged the top skater of 17 competitors in
group A while Honda, the youngest ever Japanese national
champion, was the best finisher in Group B. Honda was just a week
short of his 15th birthday.
</P>
<P>
The top 10 finishers from last year's World Championships
automatically gained berths for Wednesday's short
program. Everyone else had to go through Sunday's qualifying in
which the top 11 in each group were allowed to progress.
</P>
<P>
Galindo's group was the stronger of the two with fellow
American Dan Hollander claiming second, ahead of Guo Zhengxin of
China. Former European champion Dmitri Dmitrenko of Ukraine
finished a modest fourth.
</P>
<P>
Canadian Sebastien Britten was second behind Honda, with
Danish champion Michael Tyllesen third and Andrei Vlachtchenko of
Germany fourth.
</P>
<P>
The two women's qualifying rounds will be held on Monday with
1992 Olympic champion Midori Ito of Japan coming back to the
international tourney since the Albertville Winter Olympic Games.
</P>
</TEXT>
