<DOCNO> XIE19960318.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-18 08:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Long Journey of Pilgrimage to Lhasa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The magnificent Potala Palace and
the shining roofs of the Johkang Monastery looked so near. After
eight months' trudging, the scene was almost too good to be true
for Dungzho Doje.
</P>
<P>
"At long last we're in Lhasa," he said, with tears streaming
down his face.
</P>
<P>
Dungzho Doje, 37, is a lama with the Xiyu Monastery in Chindu
County, Qinghai Province.
</P>
<P>
He set out on his pilgrimage in July, 1995, together with his
68-year-old mother, Zhouga, and younger sister, Baima Como.
</P>
<P>
The road from Chindu to Lhasa, a holy city for Tibetans, and
the capital of the Tibet Autonomous Region, is more than 2,000
kilometers long, with an average altitude of 4,500 meters above
sea level.
</P>
<P>
Dungzho Doje said, "Winter on the plateau is bitterly old. The
freezing wind, high mountains and snow storms gave us tremendous
trouble."
</P>
<P>
"However, no difficulty on earth could waver our devotion to
Buddha," he said.
</P>
<P>
Dungzho Doje kowtowed all the way to Lhasa, a way of showing
his piousness to Buddha.
</P>
<P>
When a Tibetan Buddist kowtows, he clasps his hands, raises
them above his head, then lowers them to his chest. He does this
three times before prostrating himself on the ground. Then he
makes a mark with his stretched hands, stands up, walks to the
mark, and kowtows again.
</P>
<P>
"Before leaving for Lhasa I was so fat that a short walk made
me feel breathless," Dungzho Doje said.
</P>
<P>
"But once I made up my mind to pay the pilgrimage, nothing
could stop me," he added
</P>
<P>
Dungzho Doje, the first person in his village to make such a
pilgrimage, developed the idea during his 12 years of service as a
lama.
</P>
<P>
He said his reason of making such a pilgrimage is showing his
devotion to Buddha, as well as getting Buddha's blessings for his
mother and brothers and sisters.
</P>
<P>
When he first started the journey, he could go only one or two
km a day.
</P>
<P>
"Every day, I was aching all over, as though my back and legs
were all broken," he said. "I wasn't sure at all whether I could
reach Lhasa."
</P>
<P>
But before long, he could go eight km a day.
</P>
<P>
After a day's kowtowing, Dungzho Doje looked no better than a
beggar. Sometimes he was soaked with the snow on the road.
However, he read Buddist scriptures for three hours every night
with the help of a flashlight, no matter how tired he was.
</P>
<P>
While he kowtowed on the Qinghai-Tibet Highway, his mother and
sister would lead their donkey to where he would arrive at dusk,
erect their small tent and prepare food.
</P>
<P>
"Without the help of my mother and sister, I could never have
reached Lhasa." Dungzho Doje said.
</P>
<P>
"I also met many kind people on my way," he added. "Many truck
drivers we met gave us food, clothes and money. Some offered to
take messages to our families."
</P>
<P>
After more than eight monthes' trudging, the three pilgrims
arrived at Lhasa on March 4, and were joined by thousands of other
pilgrims from all parts of the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau.
</P>
<P>
Lhasa residents presented the pilgrims with buttered tea and
hadas, silk scarfs regarded as tokens of respect.
</P>
<P>
"The first thing we'll do this afternoon is to pay respects to
Buddha," Dungzho Doje said.
</P>
<P>
After paying respect to all the monasteries in Lhasa, he
planned to kowtow his way to Samyai, the oldest Temple in Tibet,
about 100 km south of Lhasa.
</P>
<P>
"I'll kowtow to Buddha for myself, my family and all the people
who have helped us," he said. "May Buddha bless us all." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
