<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-18 08:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economist Calls for Help for Middle and Western China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 18 (Xinhua) -- China has been urged by a leading
economist to launch a massive drive to open up the country's
hinterland areas.
</P>
<P>
The Central Government must play a key role in the initiative
which would see more railways, roads, power plants and
infrastructure projects across vast areas in central and western
parts of China, he said.
</P>
<P>
The blueprint for the hinterlands has been proposed by the
noted Chinese economist Dr Hu An'gang to spur economic growth in
underdeveloped provinces.
</P>
<P>
"China should gradually pool two thirds of investments for
public projects into the less developed central and western areas,
which are home to two thirds of China's population," said Dr. Hu
An'ang, an economist with the Chinese Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
"In areas with lower per capita gross domestic production, a
larger proportion of the investment should come from the central
government, as the underdeveloped provinces and autonomous regions
have weaker capability to accumulate capital."
</P>
<P>
Gaps in regional development have been widened in recent
years. Last year Chinese Premier Li Peng said in his government
work report to the National People's Congress that conditions be
created to narrow the gaps in regional disparities in the Ninth
Five-Year Plan (1996-2000).
</P>
<P>
In the recently-published "Regional Disparities in China", the
result of a survey on the regional development across the country
over a period of more than two years, Hu suggested that China set
up a fund for constructing railways, highways and
telecommunication facilities in the less developed regions through
issuing treasury bonds.
</P>
<P>
"Local governments should repay the principal of the fund, the
central government should pay interest on the fund, and they
should both buttress the fund with tax revenues at the same time."
</P>
<P>
"Investors should have rights to use and develop land and real
estate properties along the railways and highways," said Hu, who
was educated at America's Yale University.
</P>
<P>
"Priority should be given to arranging preferential loans from
foreign governments and international financial institutions for
the infrastructure projects, and foreign investors should be
allowed and encouraged to take part in these projects through
holding shares in, or raising funds for, these projects."
</P>
<P>
China should build more railways and highways in the central
and western regions, Hu said. "In the next ten years, China should
construct 50,000 km of railways, of which half should be in the
central and western regions."
</P>
<P>
He also proposed that China constructs on a wide scale large
power energy bases and water conservancy projects, and harness
long rivers in the interior areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960318.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-18 08:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> You Are Never Too Old to Follow Fashion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Back home from a local park in
downtown Shanghai, where 79-year-old Zhou Guoqing and his
69-year-old wife, Fei Ruilian, have been doing their morning
exercises, the old couple take a relaxing break.
</P>
<P>
Zhou sits beside Fei while she makes a carpet with some old
knitting wool, telling her the latest news he has learned.
</P>
<P>
Close by, hanging on the wall, is the latest addition to their
home, their wedding picture. It was taken just two months ago to
mark their anniversary after many years of wedded bliss.
</P>
<P>
More and more old couples like the Zhou's in Shanghai, China's
biggest city, have been pursuing an easy and romantic way of life,
with improvements in living standards.
</P>
<P>
Today it is quite common to see old couples have their wedding
pictures taken to mark anniversaries of their marriages. They
flock, often hand in hand, to one of the many luxury studios which
have sprung up in recent years.
</P>
<P>
According to a photographer at one local studio, one-fourth of
his customers wanting wedding pictures are old couples, a sharp
increase from a few years ago when few old couples sought such
pictures.
</P>
<P>
Sending gifts to each other on such occasions as birthdays, or
wedding anniversaries, has also become popular among local old
couples.
</P>
<P>
At many dance halls old couples are found dancing amid young
people during the day.
</P>
<P>
With more spare time and money these couples now are able to
take trips abroad.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot imagine having such a chance to go abroad before, as
we were busy with our work, and taking care of children," a couple
who have just applied for a 10-day trip to Thailand said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, sex, which used to be a taboo in China, has become a
open topic on the local radio station and in classes at
universities for senior citizens, which are well-received among
local old people.
</P>
<P>
Sociologists attribute this change to being aware of new ideas,
noting that it is good for their health. 
</P>
</TEXT>
