<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-18 08:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Longest Sub-marine Cable to Link China with World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 18 (Xinhua) -- China is to be given a new
high-tec link with the rest of the world by forming part of the
world's longest submerged optical cable.
</P>
<P>
The Eurasian optical cable will connect Shanghai, China's
industrial and financial center, to the world's biggest
telecommunications web.
</P>
<P>
The blueprint of the Shanghai section of FLAG, as the cable
system is known, has been unveiled by the Chinese government, said
the Communications Weekly published in the capital.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai branch cable will run into the sea via Nanhui
County, and link to the main trunk cable in the East China Sea, at
a point of 127 degrees and nine minutes east longitude, 280
degrees and 10 minutes north latitude.
</P>
<P>
The 27,000-km-long submarine cable starts at Britain, and heads
eastward, joining the Pacific submarine cable system through a
node in Japan, via a dozen countries and regions, such as Italy,
Spain, Egypt, the United Arab Emirates, India, Malaysia, Thailand,
Hong Kong, China and Republic of Korea.
</P>
<P>
Adopting the SDH (synchronous digital hierarchy) technology
which can increase its transmission speed to five Gb/s, the
fastest of the world, the Eurasian optical cable will be the
longest submarine trunk, and the last part to form a world-wide
telecommunications web.
</P>
<P>
When completed, the cable will provide more than 10,000
telephone lines to Shanghai, the paper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960318.0149 </DOCNO>
