<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign-related Taxes in Yantai Grow Steadily </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANTAI, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Beach city Yantai, in east China's
Shandong Province, collected a record 309 million yuan in
foreign-related taxes in 1995.
</P>
<P>
One of China's 50 economically most advanced cities, Yantai's
progress in collecting foreign-related tax was possible due to
entrepreneurs from 48 countries and regions which had established
3,034 foreign-funded firms by the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that an improved investment
environment has enabled more than 90 percent of the foreign-funded
firms to make profits, laying a basis for the increase in
foreign-related taxes.
</P>
<P>
To take in more foreign-related taxes, Yantai has set up
special organizations in all its districts and counties to provide
better services to foreign-related firms.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, China has given priority to upgrading
tax-collecting mechanisms in order to raise tax revenues.
</P>
<P>
In another development, Guangdong, a booming province in south
China, took in over 198 billion yuan in industrial and commercial
taxes over the past five years, with an annual growth rate of 31
percent.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong has topped all provinces in China in collecting
industrial and commercial taxes annually since 1992. Those taxes
broke the 50 billion yuan barrier in 1994 after it expanded by 10
billion yuan annually for three straight years.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Guangdong contributed 46.77 billion yuan in taxes
paid to the central government, up 23.2 percent. Over the past
five years, it has set up a tax collecting-mechanism which is in
line with a market-oriented economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
