<HEADLINE> Israel's Trade Deficit in 1995 Hits Record High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli trade deficit in
1995 hit a record high of 11.1 billion U.S. dollars, according to
the latest figures released by the Central Bureau of Statistics.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, the trade deficit was 9.4 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The figures also show that exports of goods and services
totalled 28.7 billion dollars last year, a 15 percent increase
from 24.5 billion in 1994.
</P>
<P>
However, imports last year reached 49.8 billion dollars
compared with 33.9 billion of 1994.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, foreign investments also hit a record last year,
increasing to 2 billion dollars from 600 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The advancing Middle East peace process between Israel and its
Arab neighbors has made Israel more attractive to foreign
investors. 
</P>
