<HEADLINE> More Burundi Hutus Flee Into Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 18 (Xinhua) -- More than 100 hutu
refugees have been fleeing into Tanzania daily since the
beginning of this month due to the crisis in Burundi.
</P>
<P>
Ngara District Commissioner Brigadier Sylvester Aggrey Hemed
told newsmen on the phone from Ngara in northern Tanzania on
Sunday that he has been receiving between 100 and 150 Burundi
nationals daily during the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
"The Tanzania/Burundi border is still closed. On humanitarian
ground we are being forced to allow some Burundi nationals to
cross into Tanzania," the commissioner said.
</P>
<P>
"The majority of those seeking to enter Ngara are children,
women who are still breast feeding, aged men and other women. The
horrow stories they narrate to us at border posts make us fail to
send them back," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Hemed further said the refugees alleged that Burundi
Government soldiers visited villages and killed people,
particularly members of the Hutu organization named FRODEBU
(Front Pour la Democratic au Burundi).
</P>
<P>
He added the Burundi refugees were kept at Mbuba transit point
before being moved to Keza which is close to the border with
Burundi.
</P>
<P>
He noted the fresh refugees would not be sent to the refugees
camp because some believed that the situation back home could
normalize soon. At Mbuba transit point, the refugees are given
relief services. 
</P>
</TEXT>
