<HEADLINE> Fishermen Keen to Learn Foreign Languages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Rushing to an "English corner"
on weekends on a small island off the coast of east China's
Zhejiang Province is a matter of urgency for Yao Aguo and other
villagers.
</P>
<P>
Yao, in fact, is a fisherman, and he and his friends here in
Zhoushan have decided to learn a foreign language and are trying
to practice what they've studied.
</P>
<P>
"Foreign language study is not just a fashion. Foreign
languages can be a useful tool," noted Yao.
</P>
<P>
With the booming fishery business, increasingly local people
are travelling to foreign countries in their work, and
international fishing co-operatives have mushroomed in this
province.
</P>
<P>
So, the villagers, especially the younger fishermen, made up
their minds to learn a foreign language in order to pave the way
for further co-operation with overseas business people.
</P>
<P>
In Zhoushan's Putou District, 27 language programs that were
started by the local government have helped more than 1,000
fishermen learn to speak fluent English.
</P>
<P>
Toting their English text books with them whenever they go, the
fishermen learn the language using self-study methods and by
practising what they've learned in direct contacts with foreign
fishermen.
</P>
<P>
Yuan Liwei often goes to foreign countries on his fishing
voyages. In explaining his motive for studying a foreign language,
he says, "I want to learn English so as to lay a good foundation
for understanding foreign countries and people, as well as for
business affairs."
</P>
<P>
He has also found that languages are a direct means of
communication in negotiations and exchanges in his work. 
</P>
</TEXT>
