<HEADLINE> China's Exim Bank Extends Loans to Local Power Plant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The building of a new power
station, to ease Beijing's electricity bottleneck, has moved a
stage nearer.
</P>
<P>
The Export and Import Bank of China is expected to arrange 24.6
billion yen (about 234 million US dollars) in loans for the
building of the plant in north China's Hebei Province.
</P>
<P>
The Exim Bank will extend the loans, provided by the Overseas
Economic Cooperation Fund of Japan, to the Sanhe Power Plant in
Hebei, according to an agreement signed between the bank and the
plant.
</P>
<P>
A key project listed in China's Ninth Five-Year Plan
(1996-2000) blueprint, the plant will ease the bottleneck effects
in electricity supply in Beijing after it is put into operation.
</P>
<P>
Lei Zuhua, president of the bank, said that the bank "has
introduced loans offered by governments in Japan, Germany,
Finland, Australia, Denmark, Kuwait, Norway, the Netherlands, and
Austria, as well as the North Europe Investment Bank into China."
</P>
<P>
To date, the bank has transferred 2.3 billion US dollars in
such loans to 68 projects in electricity, railway, ports, urban
infrastructure, posts and telecommunications, agriculture, and
forestry, and nearly 40 percent of the loans has gone into
electricity-related projects.  
</P>
