<HEADLINE> Beijing to Provide More Convenient Postal Services </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 18 (Xinhua) -- More than 95 percent of letters
posted in China's capital will reach their city destinations the
next day.
</P>
<P>
The first-class postal service is part of a city-wide drive to
provide a better and more efficient service.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing Postal and Telecommunication Administration has set
itself a series of goals in 1996 to provide more convenient
services, the "Beijing Daily" reports.
</P>
<P>
Postal service will be available in 1,000 more residential
buildings and 100 new postal offices will be built across the
city, bringing the ratio of residential buildings having postal
offices from 50 percent to 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
The number of post offices operating with computers will rise
to 25, and 40 postal saving units will be added to the saving
network, enabling people to get cash in at any of the network's
140 units.
</P>
<P>
Ten newspaper and periodical wholesale centers, and five postal
kiosks will be built, as well as 20 newspaper-reading boards.
</P>
<P>
Various new postal services will also be available, with 95
percent of Beijing letters reaching their inner-city destinations
within the next day, and all emergency posts arriving in their
destinations directly and safely.  
</P>
</TEXT>
