<HEADLINE> More Women in Hunan Freed From Illiteracy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Small shopkeeper Xu Yuexiang, a
woman in Taoyuan County in central China's Hunan Province, no
longer needs to ask others to do her bookkeeping.
</P>
<P>
She is one of the nearly 800,000 women in Hunan who have
learned how to read and write in a campaign aimed at sweeping away
illiteracy. Xu is also learning to write so she can send letters
to her husband, a long-distance truck driver.
</P>
<P>
According to a national census, Hunan had 1.54 million
illiterate young people in 1990, a million of them women.
</P>
<P>
Local education and women's organizations put emphasis on
helping young women learn how to read and write. Farmers' schools
have been set up in more than 3,000 townships and counties across
the province, with over 8,700 full-time teachers and more than
12,000 part-time teachers. Textbooks suitable for rural women have
been printed, helped by activities to encourage women to learn how
to read and write.
</P>
<P>
In Hengshan County alone, over 11,000 illiterate young women
have learned how to read and write. About 95 percent of them are
engaged business, or sideline production work alongside their
housework, and the majority of them are doing well in their
neighborhoods. 
</P>
</TEXT>
