<HEADLINE> Expert Warns of More Shark Attacks in HK Waters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The fatal shark attacks in
waters around Sai Kung which caused the deaths of three people in
June last year could happen again this year, an Australian expert
warned yesterday.
</P>
<P>
Vic Hislop, a veteran great shark hunter, also accused the HK
authorities of failing to act and prevent such attacks.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Hong Kong newspaper Eastern Express
yesterday, Hislop said that further complacency could lead to more
deaths in the coming months, as the South China Sea warms and
sharks migrate towards Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Hislop believes the same great white shark that was responsible
for the deaths will return and the best solution of the matter is
to kill the shark.
</P>
<P>
After a summer season featuring shark attack fears, the Urban
Council awarded last November two contracts worth about 40 million
HK dollars to fence off waters at 11 beaches in the area.
</P>
<P>
Armed police were sent out in patrol boats with orders to kill
the killer shark or sharks. Some of the beaches have nets in
place to keep the sharks away from the bathers.
</P>
<P>
Following last year's fatal attacks, the Regional Council
called for nets to be installed at all Hong Kong beaches. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
