<HEADLINE> Israel Closes Down 2 Suspected Hamas Financial Bases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Israel has closed down two
suspected Hamas financial bases -- the Holy Land Fund in
Jerusalem and the Islamic Relief Committee in Nazareth -- as part
of the continuing crackdown on the Islamic extremist organization.
</P>
<P>
According to Israeli reports, the Israeli police and army made
the move against the two institutions on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The police confiscated documents from the Holy Land Fund,
which investigators hope will allow them to locate the exact
sources of Hamas funding.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli government is demanding foreign governments close
down those sources, which are believed to come from the United
States and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
The Holy Land Fund, located in Beit Hanina neighborhood, is
the second Hamas-affiliated organization shut down in Jerusalem
since the Dizengoff bombing on March 4. Police sources said more
Hamas-affiliated groups in the city also face closure soon.
</P>
<P>
The closure was for 14 days, but the Israeli army would also
consider shutting down the office for one year. The Holy Land
Fund directors were given 96 hours to appeal the closure.
</P>
<P>
In Nazareth, the police confiscated thousands of shekels in
cash as well as hundreds of checks, documents, fax machines,
computers and other office equipment.
</P>
<P>
The measure was taken in accordance with orders issued by
Defense Minister Shimon Peres and Head of Northern Command of the
Israeli army, Amiram Levine.
</P>
<P>
The raid followed investigations lasting over a year into the
activities of the Relief Committee.
</P>
<P>
The relief organization is believed to be responsible for
transferring millions of shekels to families of Hamas activists.
</P>
</TEXT>
