<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-18 07:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Islamabad Residents Plagued by Pollen (By Hu Xiaoming) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Ambreen Khalid, the 24-year-old
daughter of a Pakistani businessman, died in Islamabad last
Thursday night after being attacked by asthma caused by pollen
allergy.
</P>
<P>
On the same night, 360 people with pollen allergy syndromes
reported at the city's Pakistan Institute of Medical Science
(PIMS) alone, which had to declare a state of emergency to deal
with the crisis.
</P>
<P>
At least seven people have reportedly died of pollen allergy so
far in the worst outbreak of this yearly scourge in the Pakistani
capital, where beautiful flowers in the full spring are making a
curse of life to the residents.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of pollen allergy patients, complaining of running
nose, sneezing, itchiness in the eyes, cough, skin irritation and
asthma attacks, are visiting hospitals for treatment on a daily
basis.
</P>
<P>
Unfortunately, doctors are not able to prescribe any wonder
drug to soothe the suffering of patients.
</P>
<P>
"One cannot do much to stop these allergies when the patients
come at the peak of the spring. By this time, the allergy has
already developed and there is no set way to cure it," said Dr.
Yawar Qazi, a chest specialist at the PIMS.
</P>
<P>
"Patients should take preventive measures well before spring
sets in," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
The preventative measures suggested by doctors include using
air filters, wearing face masks, closing windows and doors tightly
and having enough rest.
</P>
<P>
On the advice of doctors, some patients have left Islamabad and
its adjoining areas to flee from the menace.
</P>
<P>
Reports say that their recovery is astonishing once they are
out of Islamabad.
</P>
<P>
A test camp will be set up Thursday at the National Institute
of Health in the capital and offer free tests on 20 allergies.
</P>
<P>
The pollen comes mainly from the paper mulberry tree, which was
introduced from the Philippines in the 1980s, according to local
press reports.
</P>
<P>
Officials at the Capital Development Authority said allergy is
also caused by weeds, shrubs, plants, ornamental flowers and other
plant families like Cyperaceae.
</P>
<P>
The greenery around the capital helps pollen to spread while
rains aggravate pollen allergy because of a higher humidity level,
said the officials.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960318.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-18 07:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pilgrimages to Lhasa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The cold winds from the
Qinghai-Tibet Plateau sweeps the grasslands in the northern part
of the Tibet Autonomous Region, reminding the herdsmen that the
pilgrimage season has arrived.
</P>
<P>
The herdsmen, finishing their work for the year, set out with
their whole families for Lhasa, their holy land.
</P>
<P>
The traditional winter pilgrimage starts in November and
usually lasts until March. The deciding factor for the return to
the grasslands is a special date on the Tibetan calendar.
</P>
<P>
Braving the freezing wind and snow, pilgrims from every corner
of Tibet trudge all the way from their homes to Lhasa, the
cultural, political and religious center of the region.
</P>
<P>
The Potala Palace, the largest temple and the holy palace in
Tibet, receives about 10,000 pilgrims everyday in winter.
</P>
<P>
These people, holding butter lamps, and swinging their prayer
wheels, wait patiently in line for their turn to pay their
respects to every hall and figure of Buddha in the palace.
</P>
<P>
Tradition requires that Tibetans make at least two visits to
the Potala Palace during their lifetime, making and redeeming
their vows to Buddha. Those who can afford it are expected to pay
their respect to the palace every winter.
</P>
<P>
The Johkang Monastery, in the center of Lhasa, and Gandain,
Sera and Zhebung monasteries, all located in the suburbs of the
city, are also places not to be missed by the pilgrims.
</P>
<P>
Their hearts and minds blessed and in peace, the pilgrims,
return to their hometowns at the end of the pilgrimage season and
start preparing for another year's hard work.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960318.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-18 07:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: China's Trans-century Goal to Succeed -- Editorials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 18 (Xinhua) -- a number of the Hong Kong-based
newspapers today carried editorials hailing the successful
conclusion of the annual sessions of China's top legislature and
advisory body, noting that China's trans-century goal will
succeed.
</P>
<P>
The editorials stressed that the Fourth Session of the Eighth
National People's Congress (NPC) and the Fourth Session of the
Eighth National Committee of the Chinese People's Political
Consultative Conference (CPPCC) that ended in Beijing on March 17
and 13 respectively will promote China's reforms and opening to
the outside world.
</P>
<P>
"Wen Wei Po" said in its editorial that the Outline of China's
Ninth Five-Year Plan (1996-2000) for National Economic and Social
Development and Long-Range Goals for the Year 2010 approved at the
current NPC session will serve as a guideline for China's overall
development, adding that it will produce significant effects on
China's modernization drive.
</P>
<P>
It said that the outline also provides an opportunity for Hong
Kong's development and that China's steady economic growth will
surely benefit Hong Kong's economy.
</P>
<P>
In an editorial, "Ta Kung Pao" said that the outline will lead
China to be a vigorous and powerful country in the next century,
which will contribute to the world peace and human progress.
</P>
<P>
It noted that during the ninth five-year plan period, the value
of China's external trade will exceed 1,700 billion US
dollars. Of the total, quite a large proportion will be managed
through Hong Kong, which will add to Hong Kong's economic
development.
</P>
<P>
It said that with the approaching of 1997, the Preparatory
Committee of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) is
accelerating its work and most of the Hong Kong people are
dedicating their efforts to Hong Kong's smooth transition.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong Commercial Daily devoted two pages to the closing
of the NPC and CPPCC sessions, saying that the sessions have set
an important guideline for China's future development.
</P>
<P>
Its editorial noted that in the next century China will be
stronger and the Chinese people will be wealthier. " China will
play a more important role in world affairs," it stressed.
</P>
<P>
On the Taiwan issue, the editorials of the three newspapers
pointed out that after Hong Kong and Macao return to the
motherland within this century, the settlement of the Taiwan issue
will be a concern to all the Chinese people both at home and
overseas.
</P>
<P>
They condemned the splitting tendencies pursued by the Taiwan
Authorities and other factions, and warned the splittists in
Taiwan not to go too far in their games.
</P>
<P>
The editorials said that Lee Tung-hui's games on "two Chinas",
"one China, one Taiwan" and "Taiwan independence" are against the
historical trend and will be doomed to failure.  
</P>
</TEXT>
