<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-18 07:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 11 Billion Yuan Investment in Jilin's Telecom Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 18 (Xinhua) -- More than 11 billion yuan is to
be invested in telecommunications in northeast China's Jilin
Province.
</P>
<P>
The investment over the next five years almost doubles the
total spent during the past five years, and will add over two
million new telephone lines to the province's exchange
capacity. Long-distance optic cables, with a combined length of
1,860 km, will also be added to Jilin's telecommunications
infrastructure, according to the "Communications Weekly".
</P>
<P>
State-of-the-art technical developments will also be adopted,
including a system to digitalize phone switching and transmission,
in countryside areas.
</P>
<P>
By the year 2000, the telephone density of the province will
increase to 13.6 telephones per 100 persons, compared with the
current 6.2 sets per 100 people. The density will be even higher
in urban areas, reaching 35 sets.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, mobile telecommunications will cover all the
province's transportation trunks and major townships, with the
walkie-talkie density in urban areas reaching 2-3 sets per 100
persons.
</P>
<P>
Yang Liansui, administrator of the province's posts and
telecommunications bureau, said that the smooth achievement of the
targets will largely depend on a sustained increase in the state's
investment, as well as further extending bank loans and overseas
capital.
</P>
<P>
He added that the province is willing to raise loans from
foreign governments, if necessary, to ensure sufficient financial
support.
</P>
<P>
The province's investment in telecommunications will climb to
22.5 billion yuan in the first decade of the 21st century, the
paper said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
