<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-18 07:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Flood Relief Projects in Fujian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Forty reservoirs are earmarked for
east China's Fujian Province as part of a province-wide flood
control system.
</P>
<P>
The proposed reservoirs will have a total storage capacity of
1.78 billion cubic meters.
</P>
<P>
More water storage reservoirs will also be constructed in dry
areas of the province.
</P>
<P>
The plans form part of Fujian's proposals for the Ninth Five
Year Plan Period between now and 2000.
</P>
<P>
The province has built a flood forecast system on the Minjiang
River. The system has already forecast many floods, and prevented
serious disasters from occuring since it became operational in
April of last year.
</P>
<P>
Fujian invested 160 million yuan in consolidating 400
kilometers of sea embankments in 1995, exceeding the annual target
by 150 percent.
</P>
<P>
A 1,000 kilometer-strong "coast great wall" to contain high sea
tides is expected to be completed this year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, work to build flood control walls along the lower
reaches of the Minjiang River, Jinjiang River and Jiulong River is
going smoothly.
</P>
<P>
Fujian started construction of 93 water storage projects and
completed 28 reservoirs with a total storage capacity of 210
million cubic meters last year
</P>
<P>
Currently, the province's 56 counties and cities, where floods
often occur, have mapped out plans on flood control. Twenty-five
of them have started construction of flood control projects.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
