<HEADLINE> Nanning Vows to Become Economic Giant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The capital city of Guangxi
Zhuang Autonomous Region is aiming to build itself into an
economic center, backed by southwest China.
</P>
<P>
Links with south China and countries in southeast Asia will add
to the city's fortunes.
</P>
<P>
A coastal and border city, Nanning has been involved in the
construction of new transportation facilities since 1990, spurring
the development of the local economy.
</P>
<P>
The city scored an annual increase of 17.13 percent in its
gross domestic product (GDP) during the Eighth Five-Year Plan
(1991-1995).
</P>
<P>
Nanning is speeding up the building of an "X"-shape high-grade
highway network, with the city itself as the center and stretching
to other major domestic cities.
</P>
<P>
Air routes link the city with Beijing, Guangzhou, Shanghai,
Kunming, Xiamen, Guilin, Hong Kong, and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
And now one out of every four families in Nanning has a
telephone, indicating a substantial growth in telecommunications
in the city.
</P>
<P>
All the factors combine to add the right climate to attract
overseas investors. Sources said that consortia from 16 countries
and regions have provided investment for the city, and the number
of foreign-funded enterprises has risen to 526.
</P>
<P>
The city government has planned to expand Nanning's urban area
to 160 sq km from 72 sq km, making the city an important sea
gateway in the southwestern part of China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
