<HEADLINE> Xiamen Plan for International Stardom as Tourist Spot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Xiamen, one of China's top-ten
holiday destinations, has drawn up a ten year plan to attract more
tourists from around the world.
</P>
<P>
The city, in east China's Fujian Province, is determined to
become known as an international scenic port city, said mayor Hong
Yongshi.
</P>
<P>
Under the five-to-ten year plan the number of overseas tourists
to the city will increase up to 20 percent a year in the next five
years. It will mean between 400,000 and 630,000 foreigners
visiting the city each year by the end of the century.
</P>
<P>
In the same period, the number of domestic tourists will grow
at an annual rate of 10 to 15 percent, attracting between 6.23 and
7.78 million people a year by 2000.
</P>
<P>
By the century's end, the city is expected to earn almost six
billion yuan a year from tourism, the plan says.
</P>
<P>
The growth rate will be slowing in the early years of the 21st
century, the plan predicts.
</P>
<P>
It estimates an annual rate of eight to 10 percent, which means
that by the year 2010, the city will be receiving 880,000 to 1.9
million overseas tourists and 13 to 20 million domestic tourists a
year, with a total tourism revenue of 17 billion to 36 billion
yuan.
</P>
<P>
A top-10 tourist city of China, Xiamen has welcomed 1.2 million
overseas and 16 million home tourists in the last five years. Its
foreign currency income from tourism has totalled 2.3 billion US
dollars.
</P>
<P>
With its rich natural attractions and varied culture heritage,
its brisk trade and overseas investment, and its developed tourism
facilities, Xiamen is determined to advance its position in the
national tourism industry. Its Mayor Hong Yongshi said Xiamen will
be built into a "scenic international port city". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
