<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-18 07:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aerial Sowing Vital to Gansu's Tree Planting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Forestry officials looked to the
sky in more ways than one when they embarked on a massive
tree-planting drive.
</P>
<P>
They decided that aerial sowing was an important alternative to
traditional planting in northwest China's Gansu Province.
</P>
<P>
But they made the trees-from-the-sky program even more
efficient by liasing with weather experts and air force officials.
</P>
<P>
It helped them work out the best time - and the best weather
conditions - for their aerial sowing expeditions.
</P>
<P>
Over the past 16 years, the province has afforested an area
approaching a million hectares by aerial sowing, turning large
tracts of barren hills into luxurious forests.
</P>
<P>
To increase the survival rate of the trees planted by this
means, local forestry departments intensified co-operation with
meteorological departments and air forces.
</P>
<P>
After carrying out a number of experiments to choose the best
sowing time, sowing amounts, sowing places and varieties of seeds,
the province now reduced the cost of aerial sowing to 7.2 yuan
(about 87 cents) per mu, only one third of the cost by artificial
planting.
</P>
<P>
In addition, various departments have set up over 30 centers
across the province to manage, and protect the growth of trees.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the province was stricken by its worst drought in 60
years, but the germination percentage in the sown area still met
the ministry-set levels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
