<HEADLINE> Taiwan-funded Enterprises Growing in Zhejiang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Large amounts of Taiwan funds
have poured into east China's Zhejiang province, making it one of
the hottest destinations for investors from across the Straits.
</P>
<P>
The province now ranks in a high spot, behind Guangdong,
Fujian, Jiangsu provinces and Shanghai along the east coast of
China.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the Provincial Taiwan Affairs Office show that
by the end of last year, 2,400 Taiwan-funded enterprises had been
approved for operation by local governments, involving a total
investment of 4.2 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
As a strong sign of improvements in the scale and quality of
investments, long-term, massive projects, each involving huge
amounts of money, have gradually taken the place of small-scale
firms. Now, 20 out of the top hundred enterprises in Taiwan have
established branches in Zhejiang.
</P>
<P>
Zhejiang province has approved 60 large-scale Taiwan-funded
projects with each involving an investment of at least 10 million
US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Another new trend is that Taiwan investors are making
additional investments, to expand profitable projects they have
run on the mainland. In 1995 alone, over 100 million US dollars
were invested to this purpose.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the flow of funds have diversified, from traditional
trades like clothing and services, to sectors like energy,
communications, and agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Experts attributed the surge of Taiwan funds in Zhejiang to an
improved investment environment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
