<DOCNO> XIE19960318.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-18 06:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanians Laud EA Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanians have lauded
the newly-founded East African Cooperation saying it was an
important historic step towards achieving African economic
independence, a local paper reported today.
</P>
<P>
In a cross-section interview with Dar es Salaam residents
here in past few days, the people felt that the re-activation of
the East African Cooperation should go further and put in place
independent institutions that would stand the test of time.
</P>
<P>
The chairman of the Party for Democracy and Progress
(CHADEMA), Edwin Mtei said, "Although they did not care to invite
me as former East African Community Secetary-General, I am
encouraged that the East African Cooperation has been possible to
build something that will be tangible for East Africans".
</P>
<P>
While agreeing that the East African Community cannot be
re-activated, Mtei said the East African heads of state should do
whatever is practicable to resuscitate some of the common
services such as railways, marine services in Lake Victoria and
post and telecommunications services.
</P>
<P>
Mr Mtei also called for relaxation of border restrictions and
liberalization of currency exchange.
</P>
<P>
He urged Tanzanians to produce goods that would sell in East
Africa#,saying, "We should be able to produce quality goods at
competitive prices. What will save us is efficiency and not a
common market".
</P>
<P>
Mtei added as former secretary-general, he would like the
East African Cooperation to bear tangible results.
</P>
<P>
A senior official of the National Convention for Construction
and Reform (NCCR-Mageuzi), Anthony Komu said cooperation in any
form was a welcome move among East Africans, adding that the East
African leaders should create independent institutions that can
be able to withstand pressures from heads of state on personal
interests.
</P>
<P>
He asked the East African presidents -- Benjamin Mkapa of
Tanzania, Yoweri Museveni of Uganda and Daniel arap Moi of Kenya
to be open, daring and foresighted if the cooperation is to bear
any positive fruits.
</P>
<P>
He cautioned, "Personal differences among East African
leaders led to the demise of the then East African Community. The
present leadership should not allow these to override East
African interests".
</P>
<P>
A Dar es Salaam trader, Abdallah Juma, said East Africans
should be able to move from one country to another with the
minimum of inconveniences from customs and immigration officials.
</P>
<P>
He also hoped for the harmonization of customs duty so as to
discourgae what he called "black transactions".
</P>
<P>
He stressed, "Smuggling can be killed if the three states
agree on common customs and tariffs as is the case with the
European Community". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
