<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-18 06:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's First Museum of Rare Stones from Northern Desert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 18 (Xinhua) -- With black eyes and a pink mouth,
a chick crouches in a white eggshell -- the object is a rare and
precious stone.
</P>
<P>
It is a natural art treasure, according to owner Zhang
Jing, an old man in his 70s.
</P>
<P>
Foreign businessmen offered one million US dollars for the
piece of agate, but Zhang refused it. It is now safely kept in the
Construction Bank of China.
</P>
<P>
China has another artificial agate chicken in the Palace
Museum.
</P>
<P>
Last October, Zhang brought thousands of precious stones,
collected in the Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region's desert, to
Beijing, and set up a museum in the capital to display the natural
arts and crafts.
</P>
<P>
The old man said "The stones collected from the desert
enthralled me because of their solid nature, rich color and unique
style."
</P>
<P>
More than 800 stones, including crystal, agate, jasper,
chalcedony and opal form Zhang's collection. Some are in the shape
of human beings, animals and flowers, and the largest weighes 350
kg.
</P>
<P>
These rare stones are silicide, according to the experts.
</P>
<P>
Zhang collected money to set up a company in Xiamen, a city in
southeast China's Fujian province in 1986, to export jade
decorations and stone carvings.
</P>
<P>
Hard work and difficult conditions are blamed for the cancer he
suffered in 1990. After an operation, he continued exerting
himself to develop the culture of the stones.
</P>
<P>
Zhang was invited to visit a Singapore museum featuring unique
stones in 1993. After his return, he had a desire to set up a
similar museum in China.
</P>
<P>
"These natural arts and crafts are an important part of
culture," the old man said, adding, "I hope to spread the unique
culture in China, even across the world."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960318.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-18 06:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Restricts Level of Petrol Aromatics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The New Zealand government has
imposed restriction on the level of aromatics in the controversial
new unleaded petrol, known as Octane 96.
</P>
<P>
Energy Minister Doug Kidd today announced that the maximum
level of aromatics in the new petrol should be 50 percent while
oil companies must lower that level to 48 percent in one month.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made after oil companies found that petrol in
some of their storage tanks contained as much as 56 percent of
aromatics.
</P>
<P>
The high level of aromatics in the new fuel is blamed for
eroding some rubber components in old cars and causing car fires
in the past weeks.
</P>
<P>
The oil companies said they were sending special deliveries of
petrol with the aromatics level below 50 percent to service
stations to replace the fuel containing a high level of aromatics.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
