<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka To Set Up Vocational Centers In Villages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan government has
decided to set up 500 vocational training centers in villages to
ensure that the country's youth will gain access to gainful
employment, according to official sources here today.
</P>
<P>
The government's move comes after a survey found that only
about three percent of the country's four million students are
admitted to universities.
</P>
<P>
There are a large number of school dropouts who can gain
vocational training and other skills, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
These centers will produce trained manpower to meet the needs
of the country's industrial sector, said the sources, adding that
there will be at least six courses at each center.
</P>
<P>
Among the courses will be welding, electrical repairs, motor
mechanism, carpentry, masonry, beauty therapy, home science bridal
dressing and radio, TV and electronic repairs.
</P>
<P>
It is now expected that about 50,000 youths in rural areas
could be provided with specialized training a year at the 500
training centers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
