<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-18 05:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 35,000 More Vietnamese Boat People to Be Sent Back Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, March 18 (Xinhua) -- About 35,000 more Vietnamese boat
people in Hong Kong, Japan and southeastern Asian countries will
be repatriated home, official sources said today.
</P>
<P>
Dinh The Lap, deputy director of the Department for Refugees
and Repatriation of the Ministry of Labor, War Invalids and
Social Affairs (MOLISA), said that the repatriation would be
conducted with the assistance from the United Nations High
Commissioner for Refugees and Repatriation (UNHCR).
</P>
<P>
There was in the mid-1980s an exodus of people who fled the
country by boats to Thailand, Hong Kong, Malaysia and other places
in the region, and their illegal departures "caused big problems"
to where they went and to the international community, Dinh said.
</P>
<P>
Most of these refugees left the country for "economic reasons,"
because they were fishermen and peasants living in coastal areas,
and handicraft-men and small traders in urban areas who lived a
hard life when the country was beset with economic difficulties in
the early 1980's, he said.
</P>
<P>
In the late 1988, with the help of some international
organizations, the Vietnamese government launched a program for
voluntary repatriation of the boat people. The Interior Ministry,
Foreign Affairs Ministry, provincial and municipal people's
committees and the MOLISA were asked to get involved in the
program.
</P>
<P>
The government adopted a lenient policy toward the returnees,
promising not to punish them for their illegal departures but to
provide them with assistance that would help stabilize their life
in the country.
</P>
<P>
As a result, some 77,000 boat people have returned from refugee
camps abroad and returned to normal life in their home country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960318.0196 </DOCNO>
