<HEADLINE> Opposition Enforces Mass Curfew in Bangladeshi Port </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's opposition parties
have decided to start a "mass curfew" today in the country's
largest port of Chittagong, where the government had deployed navy
forces to try to restore its operation Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made Sunday at a meeting of the port city's
All-Party Action Committee presided over by Chittagong Mayor and
opposition leader A.B.M. Mohiuddin Chowdhury.
</P>
<P>
The committee resolved to scale up the opposition's current
"non-cooperation" campaign against the government to press for the
cancellation of the February 15 parliamentary polls and fresh
elections under a neutral caretaker government.
</P>
<P>
It sought the solidarity of all those concerned with the port
and urged them not to cooperate with the government.
</P>
<P>
Reports said the Chittagong port, the country's largest
commercial lifeline, still remained almost paralyzed by the
opposition's strike-like campaign despite the deployment of the
navy forces.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, an official release said shipping services at the port
had returned to normal Sunday.  
