<HEADLINE> Law Makers From EU, Central, East Europe End Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Parliamentarians from the European
Union and central and east European countries ended their meeting
here today after discussing the role of parliaments in European
integration and the EU's extension to eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
During their three-day meeting, many representatives demanded
that the parliaments of the EU member countries get involved in
the EU summit to be held in Turin, Italy, on March 29. The summit
will discuss and amend the Maastricht Treaty.
</P>
<P>
President of the European Parliament Klaus Hansch also asked
those parliaments to send observers to the summit.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, Austrian National Council President Heinz
Fischer spoke against European integration by some countries
first. "We must prevent the EU member countries from being divided
into different ranks," he said. The structural reform in the EU
should not harm the rights of small countries.
</P>
<P>
On the EU's extension to the east, Fischer said the EU does not
have the capability to accept east European countries whose
political and economic conditions are not qualified for the EU
membership.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, Hansch and Fischer announced a joint
statement, stressing that the Turin summit would be a milestone in
the EU and European development and its task would be to create
conditions for the EU's eastern extension.
</P>
<P>
Forty-five parliamentarians from the EU, central and east
European countries attended the meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960318.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-18 04:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Prime Minister on EU, Domestic Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 17 (Xinhua) -- French Prime Minister Alain Juppe
stressed today that the European Union (EU) must undergo reforms
before its possible eastern expansion.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in a TV interview, Juppe said only a united Europe can
maintain its strength and prosperity.
</P>
<P>
He suggested that the EU summit scheduled for March 29 in
Turin, Italy, should discuss how to manage the 15-member union
smoothly and establish new common mechanisms on a single currency,
joint defense and foreign policies.
</P>
<P>
Some east European countries, especially Germany's neighbors,
have asked for EU membership. But France, worried that their entry
will lead to a more powerful Germany, is reluctant to accept them
as new companions.
</P>
<P>
On the domestic economy, the prime minister, who had proclaimed
"spring is coming" two days before, insisted that he can see the
first signs of recovery. "I promise that there are positive
signs," said Juppe.
</P>
<P>
In particular he pointed to a fall in interest rates, a
reduction in long-term unemployment, boosted consumer spending and
a fresh enthusiasm among investors.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister, who told the audience that he does not want
to be "a weather forecaster," predicted that France and Germany
will have seen a favorable turn in their economies by the end of
1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
