<HEADLINE> Legal Aid Proposed for Thai Overseas Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The Thai Justice Ministry is
proposing posting legal advisers abroad to protect Thai overseas
workers in the wake of the execution of five Thai workers in
Singapore last week on charges of murder and robbery.
</P>
<P>
Justice Minister Chalerm Yubamrung said Sunday he would submit
a proposal Tuesday to Prime Minister Banharn Silpa-Archa for
posting legal advisers to those countries or regions where there
are significant numbers of Thai workers.
</P>
<P>
Chalerm is scheduled to meet Singaporean diplomats in Bangkok
Tuesday on the issue of four other Thais on death row in
Singapore.
</P>
<P>
Overseas Thai workers have no access to immediate legal advice
when they have legal problems while most court cases are almost
over before they reach the Thai government, said Chalerm.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government is now under fire for paying scant
attention to the plight of Thais working aboard.  
</P>
</TEXT>
