<HEADLINE> Ribeiro Wins Indy's Brazil Debut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Brazilian Andre Ribeiro
gave something to cheer for his compatriots here Sunday by winning
the inaugural Rio 400, the first Indy-car race in South America.
</P>
<P>
Ribeiro led the final 18 laps of the race to beat runner-up Al
Unser Snr by 2.141 seconds and give enginemaker Honda a second
victory in as many events this season.
</P>
<P>
Jimmy Vasser won the opener with Honda power two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
Seven of the top 12 finishers were grabbed by the Brazilians
here at the first race.
</P>
<P>
Italian rookie Alex Zanardi, the pole-sitter, was fourth behind
Ribiero, Unser and American Scott Pruett, who took the series lead
by a point over Vasser entering race three on March 31 in
Australia. 
</P>
