<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-18 02:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Communist Party Leader Outlines Election Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Russian Communist Party leader
Gennady Zyuganov set out his election program Sunday, offering not
to restore the Soviet Union by force, the Itar-Tass news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Outlining his program for running for the presidency, Zyuganov,
51, stressed that he favors the resolutions approved by the State
Duma (the lower house of Parliament) Friday that denounced the
1991 accords that led to the dissolution of the former Soviet
Union. But, he said, this does not mean that "tomorrow someone will
forcibly annex anyone's territory or encroach on anyone's
sovereignty."
</P>
<P>
He said that all necessary measures would be taken for a
voluntary restoration of all contacts between Russia, Ukraine,
Belarus and Kazakhstan -- the "big four" among the 12 members of
the Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS). Three other former
Soviet republics, the Baltic states of Lithuania, Latvia and
Estonia have refused to join the CIS.
</P>
<P>
The Party leader also offered to bring an end to the
15-month-long war in the breakaway Chechnya and prevent fresh
military conflicts in Russia.
</P>
<P>
He promised to "guarantee the right of all citizens to work,
rest, housing and free education" if he wins the June 16
elections.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he offered "to bring wages, salaries, pensions and
student grants into line with real subsistence minimum" and "to
make up for savings lost by the depositors as a result of the
so-called reforms." He also promised to work for family, mother
and child welfare and secure a radical change in the position of
women in society.
</P>
<P>
Zyuganov announced an intention to uphold the interests of
the home producers at enterprises of all forms of ownership and
take urgent measures and apply a state regulation of the economy
if necessary.
</P>
<P>
He promised to save the country's scientific, technical and
cultural potential and give state support to high-tech plants in
the defense sector.
</P>
<P>
His program contains a promise to strengthen the financial
system, ensure the stability of the rouble, establish state
monopoly on foreign trade in natural resources and strategic
commodities. He recognized the multi-structural character of the
economy, with the state retaining the management of strategically
important sectors.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, measures will be taken to fight corruption in the
state apparatus.
</P>
<P>
As for his foreign policy, Zyuganov noted it will be "an active
one." "We shall not stop short of terminating inequitable
treaties which infringe upon the interests" of Russia, he added.
</P>
<P>
Alexander Rutskoi, Russia's former Vice-President and leader
of the "Derzhava" (Great Power) national-patriotic movement,
today announced his support for the candidacy of Zyuganov as a
single candidate from the national-patriotic forces.
</P>
<P>
Zyuganov, who is the presidential candidate from a so-called
"bloc of national-patriotic forces" with his Communist Party as
the main force, has been regarded here as the most strong rival
for President Boris Yeltsin, who has decided to run for a second
term of office in order to safeguard the ongoing reforms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
