<HEADLINE> Chang Beats Haarhuis in Champions Cup Tennis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Fifth seed Michael Chang of
the United States captured his second career Champions Cup title
by beating Paul Harrhuis of the Netherlands 7-5, 6-1, 6-1 Sunday
in the final of the 1.95 million U.S. dollars Champions Cup in
Indian Wells, Calif.
</P>
<P>
Chang, who ousted world number three and third seed Andre
Agassi in the quarter-finals, needed just an hour and 52 minutes
to wrap up the best-of-five-set contest.
</P>
<P>
He earned 320,000 dollars for the victory in the first of the
ATP Tour's "Super 9" events of the year.
</P>
<P>
Haarhuis had beaten three top-10 players to reach the final,
including world number-two and top seed Pete Sampras, the two-time
defending champion who fell in the quarter-finals.
</P>
<P>
In the semi-finals he beat sixth-seeded Croatian Goran
Ivanisevic, winner of four tournaments this year, and he beat
number nine Thomas Enqvist of Sweden in the second round.
</P>
<P>
Chang stretched his career record against Haarhuis to 5-1. With
the win he will move ahead of Germany's Boris Becker, a
second-round loser, to number four in the world rankings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
