<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-18 01:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Terra-cotta Warriors Don't Win Fight Alone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Shaanxi Province, site of the
2,200-year-old terra-cotta warriors and the tombs of 73 emperors,
is relying for its long-term prosperity on applied science and
technology, not just tourism, "China Daily" reports.
</P>
<P>
"As a major high-tech base Shaanxi developed China's first
planes, rockets, colour TV tubes and integrated circuits," said
Governor Cheng Andong.
</P>
<P>
The province has over 1,000 research institutes, 56
universities and a high-powered labour pool including 820,000
professionals, giving it a research strength second only to that
found in Beijing and Shanghai, he said.
</P>
<P>
An industrial development belt is emerging between the
provincial capital of Xi'an and Baoji, about 300 kilometres to its
west.
</P>
<P>
Cheng predicted that five years from now, 10 group
companies--contributing 50 billion yuan(6.02 billion US dollars)
in added industrial value and five billion yuan taxes
annually--will have taken shape there.
</P>
<P>
One high-tech focus will be the province's drought-stricken
agriculture, he said.
</P>
<P>
This northwestern province is considering co-operating with the
Ministry of Water Resources to carry out a water-diversion project.
</P>
<P>
The project is expected to turn 1.33 million hectares of dry
farm land into irrigated land and to relieve the shortage of
drinking water in Xi'an.
</P>
<P>
A demonstration farm, Yangling High-tech Agricultural
Development Zone, which is scheduled to cover 20 sq km, is being
created along the Xi'an-Baoji industrial development belt.
</P>
<P>
Since the discovery and excavation of the terra-cotta warriors
in the 1970s, tourism has remained one of Shaanxi's pillar
industries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960318.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-18 01:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Steps Up Pollution Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Beijing is expected to launch 10
environmental protection projects this year in a bid to control
dust discharge, air and noise pollution, and protect underground
and surface water resources.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1996 dust discharge in the Shijingshan District,
where many large industrial plants are situated, will be cut by
5,500 tons, the national English-language newspaper China Daily
reports today.
</P>
<P>
"Around 15 factories and workshops causing serious air, water
or noise pollution will be ordered to stop production or move out
of the urban area by December 31," the paper quoted an assistant
mayor as saying.
</P>
<P>
Another 50 sources of heavy industrial pollution will be
cleaned up or relocated within specific time limits in 1996, the
official said.
</P>
<P>
More than 120 factories and workshops have left the capital
city since the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
Safe disposal of solid wastes will be enhanced, and the
suburban area controlled by noise pollution measures will be
expanded by 15 sq.km.
</P>
<P>
He said "controlling the discharge of pollutants is one of the
most important tasks for the municipal government in the next five
years".  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
