<DOCNO> XIE19960318.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-18 01:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Observatories to Observe Hale-Bopp </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 18 (Xinhua) -- China's major observatories have
set up a coordination group in Shanghai to jointly observe the
Hale-Bopp comet as it approaches the Earth.
</P>
<P>
The coordination group, consisting of the Shanghai, Yunnan,
Purple Mountain and Beijing Observatories, and the Chinese
University of Science and Technology, will use over a dozen
telescopes to observe the comet, which has a cycle of some 4,200
years.
</P>
<P>
It will be the third time observatories have launched joint
observation exercises in China. Sky-watchers worked together to
observe Haley's Comet and the crash between Shoemaker-Levy and
Jupiter.
</P>
<P>
Hale-Bopp will keep a distance of 150 million km from the Earth
when it reaches the perigee, and will have no direct influence on
the latter, according to researchers of the Shanghai Observatory.
</P>
<P>
At present, the Shanghai and Yunnan Observatories have shot
several useful pictures of the approaching Hale-Bopp comet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
