<HEADLINE> Italian Soccer Players on Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Rome, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of soccer-mad Italians
were deprived of their favorite sport Sunday as the country's
highly paid professional soccer players staged their first ever
strike.
</P>
<P>
The players announced the strike last week to press for a
greater say in the running of their sport, the immediate abolition
of transfer fees and the creation of a solidarity fund for players
in financial difficulty.
</P>
<P>
Many unhappy fans were forced to spend the day indoors with
their families by a combination of bad weather and the absence of
soccer.
</P>
<P>
The organization said Sunday's strike was a "clear
demonstration of bad management" in the sport.
</P>
<P>
Most of the Serie A clubs devoted the day to training, with Ac
Milan preparing for its Uefa Cup quarterfinal against Bordeaux
Tuesday and Juventus for a Champions' Cup clash against Real
Madrid Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated the strike will cost the Italian Olympic
Committee, which finances other sports from official gambling on
the soccer results, around d40 million in lost earnings but the
money should be made up when the day's matches are rescheduled at
the end of the season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
