<HEADLINE> Chinese Newspaper Highlights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
"People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- The National People's Congress (NPC), China's top
legislative body, concluded its annual plenary session yesterday
by adopting a blueprint for the nation's development through the
next 15 years.
</P>
<P>
Qiao Shi, chairman of the NPC Standing Committee, described the
Outline of the Ninth Five-Year Plan (1996-2000) and the Long-Term
Target for the Year 2010, --endorsed by the Fourth Plenary Session
of the Eighth NPC held from March 5 to 17 in Beijing-- as the
"most splendid" trans-century document ever seen in Chinese
history.
</P>
<P>
-- An editorial carried on this leading newspaper in China
hails the successful conclusion of the Fourth Session of the NPC
and the Fourth Session of the Eighth National Committee of the
Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC) ended
in Beijing on March 17 and March 13 respectively.
</P>
<P>
The editorial notes that the two sessions have made historical
contributions to China's reform, opening-up and modernization
drive.
</P>
<P>
"Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese Premier Li Peng said at a press conference yesterday
that with regard to the Taiwan Question, the Communist Party of
China and the Chinese government do not change their basic
principles of peaceful reunification and of "one country, two
systems."
</P>
<P>
The eight-point proposals put forward by the Chinese President
Jiang Zemin one year ago made overall and profound explanations on
the principles, Li Peng said.
</P>
<P>
"China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- A spokesman for the Chinese Foreign Ministry on Saturday
refuted a report alleging that China has told the US it will not
resort to the use of arms in the Taiwan issue.
</P>
<P>
Shen Guofang, the ministry spokesman, said "The report is
groundless" when asked to comment on the assertion.  
</P>
</TEXT>
