<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kabbah Wins S. Leone's Presidential Runoff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Tejan Kabbah, leader of the
Sierra Leone People's Party (SLPP), has won the presidential runoff,
said an official announcement here tonight.
</P>
<P>
Kabbah score 608,419 votes (59.49 percent), defeating
81-year-old Karefa-Smart, leader of the United National People's
Party (UNPP), according to an announcement broadcast tonight by
the Electoral Commission through the state radio.
</P>
<P>
Karefa-Smart polled 414,335 votes (40.51 percent) in the
second round of the presidential election done on March 15,
according to James Jonah, chairman of the Electoral Commission.
</P>
<P>
The total casted votes are 1,227,540 but don't include two
polling stations in the Koinadugu District in the far north of
the country.
</P>
<P>
"Results from these two stations will in no way affect the
general voting trend," said Jonah, who is also a former assistant
secretary general of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Kabbah had also led Karefa-Smart in the first round of the
presidential election on February 26 and 27 but fell short of
emerging a winner of the election.
</P>
<P>
He had won 35.8 percent of the vote while Karefa-Smart had
gained 22.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to the constitution of the West African state, a
president elect must get at least 55 percent of the votes.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the two candidates had to run the second round of
the election last Friday.
</P>
<P>
However, bad road conditions and poor communication facilities
prevented most of the votes being brought to the Freetown,
capital of the West African state, from remote areas until
Saturday and early today.
</P>
<P>
Political observers said it is still not clear when the
military government led by Brigadier General Julius Maada Bio,
would hand over to the new civilian government.But State house
sources said privately that it will be done within 21 days.
</P>
<P>
This is the second time the SLPP comes to power. The oldest
party of Sierra Leone brought the country to independence in
1961. But in 1967, it was defeated by the All People's Congress
which was overthrown by the military in 1992. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960318.0233 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-17 22:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hague Tribunal Wants to Open Office in Serb State </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, March 17 (Xinhua) -- A senior official of the
Hague-based international tribunal proposed today to set up an
office in Bosnian Serb state.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prosecutor of the International War Crimes Tribunal for
the former Yugoslavia Graham Blewitt made the proposal at a
meeting with Serb Prime Minister Rajko Kasagic in Pale, the Serb
stronghold east of Sarajevo, Tanjug news agency said.
</P>
<P>
Blewitt told reporters after the meeting that he expected an
affirmative reply to the proposal from the Serb authorities.
</P>
<P>
Blewitt said his talks with Serb officials were very important
since it had laid a firm foundation for the tribunal's
investigation in Republika Srpska, which would cover victims and
witnesses of crimes against Serbs.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Kasagic said the tribunal had asked for Serb
cooperation and proposed that tribunal's experts be able to
question witnesses and victims of crimes against Serbs.
</P>
<P>
The tribunal also asked to be given access to mass graves and
to be permitted to make exhumations in order to gather evidence
about crimes against Serbs, the Serb premier said, adding that the
Serb authority was yet to give a definite answer to the requests
and proposals made by the tribunal's officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
