<HEADLINE> ADB Provides 2.7 Billion-Dollar Loan To Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The African Development Bank (ADB)
has provided 2.7 billion U.S. Dollars to a number of projects in
Nigeria, Omar Kabbaj, president of the bank, announced today.
</P>
<P>
The bank chief was quoted today by the News Agency of Nigeria
as saying in Abuja, capital of Nigeria as saying that the bank
had already disbursed 1.5 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
And the balance of 1.2 billion U.S. Dollars, which is yet to
be disbursed, would form part of the issues slated for talks with
the nigerian government, he added.
</P>
<P>
"Nigeria is a very important member of the bank and I will
always ensure that the bank contributes to its growth and
progress," said Kabbaj, a Moroccan who was elected the ADB
president last August.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria is now the greatest shareholder of ADB with over 10
percent share in the bank.
</P>
<P>
The ADB chief is current in Nigeria for talks with the Abacha
administration on expending the bank's funds to the
infrastructure building of the West African state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
