<HEADLINE> Cyprus Cabinet Discusses EU course </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus Council of Ministers
today held a special session to discuss the island's course
toward the European Union (EU) and expressed satisfaction over
the work done so far on the EU harmonization.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the press after a 90-minute meeting, Foreign
Minister Alecos Michaelides said he presented before the council
a general picture of the various plans prepared so far but
emphasis was given on the Cypriot contribution to the structured
dialogue with the EU and the harmonization process.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, the structured dialogue is an
opportunity for the Cypriot ministers to have contacts with their
EU counterparts, in a bid to learn the problems, the views and
the issues associated with the acquis communautaire.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, it is an opportunity for the island's
ministers to project progress made by Cyprus and what it was
doing in its effort to be fully harmonized with Europe.
</P>
<P>
Michaelides noted that today's cabinet meeting was the
beginning of a series of similar meetings aimed at examining
Cyprus' course toward the EU, during which the government will
be checking whether its targets set within the framework of the
structured dialogue, are being fulfilled.
</P>
<P>
The minister said a total of 21 working groups was working in
various ministries, preparing the ground for Cyprus' smooth entry
into the EU.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that all ministers attending the meeting had
reported to the council about the work done in their respective
ministries in this direction.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus, which has been divided since the 1974 Turkish
invasion, applied for the EU full membership in July 1990.
</P>
<P>
The EU Council of Ministers decided in March 6, 1995 to start
accession talks with Cyprus six months after the EU
Intergovernmental Conference scheduled for this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
