<HEADLINE> Greek Noble Laureate Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Greek Nobel laureate Odysseus
Elytis died here today of heart failure at the age of 85.
</P>
<P>
Born in Heraklion, Crete in 1911, he was awarded the 1979 Nobel
Prize for literature.
</P>
<P>
His most important works include "Axion Esti,"
"Prosanatolismi", "Maria-Nefeli," "Ta Ro Tou Erota" and "Hlios O
Hliatoras".
</P>
<P>
Renowed Greek composers Mikys Theodorakis and Manos Hatzidakis
put many of his works to music.
</P>
<P>
Elytis also wrote essays and translated poetry.
</P>
<P>
In 1936, Elytis left the Athens University Law School and
joined the military.
</P>
<P>
In 1948 Elytis left Greece for Paris where he established ties
with the French modernist poets and artists. He returned to Greece
in 1951 after spending three years of travelling in France, Spain,
Britain and Italy.
</P>
<P>
Until the fall of the Greek Junta in 1974, Elytis travelled
abroad, wrote and published poetry.
</P>
<P>
Upon returning to Greece he was appointed president of the
governing board of the National T.V. and Radio Foundation, and a
member of the Board of the National Theatre.
</P>
<P>
Inspired by the Greek tradition and folklore, Elytis focused
through his poetry on the struggle of contemporary man.
</P>
<P>
His funeral will take place on Tuesday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
